00:29:09.470 --> 00:29:11.450
They were a military state.

00:29:11.450 --> 00:29:16.890
It's been said that, you know,
some countries have an army.

00:29:16.890 --> 00:29:19.630
Well, this army has a country.

00:29:19.630 --> 00:29:21.950
And that sort of belief was carried

00:29:21.950 --> 00:29:26.160
on into German culture
at the time here.

00:29:29.310 --> 00:29:34.730
So now, let's have an
overview of military maps.

00:29:34.730 --> 00:29:38.750
What they did -- how they
were using the result of them.

00:29:38.750 --> 00:29:43.190
I call this a military
mapping revolution.

00:29:43.190 --> 00:29:45.400
What do I mean by that?

00:29:45.400 --> 00:29:53.190
Well, never before was information
about the field of battle,

00:29:53.190 --> 00:29:59.260
its scope, the particular details
of the train, the obstacles

00:29:59.260 --> 00:30:06.290 position:56%
and the enemy formations given to a
junior officer in a map form before.

00:30:06.290 --> 00:30:10.900
In World War I, millions
of maps were produced.

00:30:10.900 --> 00:30:14.930
The U.S. Army alone produced 3.5
million maps for its own forces,

00:30:14.930 --> 00:30:20.270
and it was just there from
1917 until November 11, 1918.

00:30:20.270 --> 00:30:25.240 position:56%
Maps were made every day of the war,
often updated every day of the war,

00:30:25.240 --> 00:30:29.410
a very detailed level
of intelligence.

00:30:29.410 --> 00:30:34.130
So, we're going to talk about,
what were they looking for?

00:30:34.130 --> 00:30:37.100
They were looking for the enemy's
artillery, their trench lines,

00:30:37.100 --> 00:30:40.240
obstacles, routes in and out,

00:30:40.240 --> 00:30:41.650
and something called
"the order of battle."

00:30:41.650 --> 00:30:44.740
That means, who are the enemy
troops, how strong are they,

00:30:44.740 --> 00:30:46.610
how long have they
been in the battle,

00:30:46.610 --> 00:30:49.960
and what's the overall situation?

00:30:49.960 --> 00:30:51.750
How is that information gathered?

00:30:51.750 --> 00:30:56.350
Through reconnaissance,
direct observation by people

00:30:56.350 --> 00:31:00.210
on the ground, and
aerial photographs.

00:31:00.210 --> 00:31:03.610
Prisoners, of course, were an
important source of information.

00:31:03.610 --> 00:31:10.870
Sometimes they willingly gave it
over for a sandwich and a cigar.

00:31:10.870 --> 00:31:13.390
Defectors and spies.

00:31:13.390 --> 00:31:17.950
And the result of all this was
that tremendous tactical mapping

00:31:17.950 --> 00:31:21.270
at a very scale, high level
of detail, and it allowed

00:31:21.270 --> 00:31:25.880
for massive deployments
of troops and bombardments

00:31:25.880 --> 00:31:29.640
that were beyond what
the eye could see.

00:31:29.640 --> 00:31:34.520
As you know in historic battles,
such as the Revolutionary War,

00:31:34.520 --> 00:31:37.740
the Civil War, the Napoleonic
War, the general himself would get

00:31:37.740 --> 00:31:39.410
on a horse and serve
at the battlefield,

00:31:39.410 --> 00:31:41.630
and be able to see everything.

00:31:41.630 --> 00:31:45.190
Well, these battles are stretching
for miles and miles and miles.

00:31:45.190 --> 00:31:47.640
One general cannot
see what's going on.

00:31:47.640 --> 00:31:48.950
He needs a map.

00:31:48.950 --> 00:31:52.290
And then, for the subordinates
in the field to understand

00:31:52.290 --> 00:31:55.890 position:56%
and to translate his orders into
action, they need a map that relates

00:31:55.890 --> 00:31:58.610
to their particular situation.

00:31:58.610 --> 00:32:01.510
And this resulted in some
of the deadliest battles

00:32:01.510 --> 00:32:03.810
in the history of warfare.

00:32:07.280 --> 00:32:12.750
When the war began,
however, in 1914,

00:32:12.750 --> 00:32:14.980
they were making all these
great big strategic plans

00:32:14.980 --> 00:32:16.280
like the von Schlieffen plan.

00:32:16.280 --> 00:32:18.850
The other countries had their
plans and they were wrapping

00:32:18.850 --> 00:32:22.100
up their militaries with
the latest weaponry.

00:32:22.100 --> 00:32:27.510
But the mapping effort was
not on par with that energy.

00:32:28.560 --> 00:32:31.810
When both sides went to war,
they were relying on maps

00:32:31.810 --> 00:32:37.160
that were printed in the 1880s
that were these large-scale maps.

00:32:37.160 --> 00:32:40.970
And when I talk about map scale,

00:32:40.970 --> 00:32:43.210
think of it like this
-- one to one is unity.

00:32:43.210 --> 00:32:44.510
It's the same.

00:32:44.510 --> 00:32:48.730
And the more you move away from
that, you're able to show more

00:32:48.730 --> 00:32:50.350
of the earth, but in less detail.

00:32:50.350 --> 00:32:53.790
So this is showing
1 to 8000 in France.

00:32:53.790 --> 00:32:58.670
And this is a great regional
picture, but if you are asked

00:32:58.670 --> 00:33:01.620
to go take the enemy dug out, well,

00:33:01.620 --> 00:33:03.420
where's even the trench
line on this map?

00:33:03.420 --> 00:33:05.100
It would be so small.

00:33:05.100 --> 00:33:08.490 position:56%
It's useless for a tactical purpose.

00:33:11.100 --> 00:33:14.360
So it took them two
years to get things right

00:33:14.360 --> 00:33:17.560
on both sides on the Western front.

00:33:17.560 --> 00:33:19.430
They developed things
called tactical maps,

00:33:19.430 --> 00:33:21.280
which I've talked about.

00:33:21.280 --> 00:33:23.450
So for the infantry, the
guy fighting on the ground,

00:33:23.450 --> 00:33:25.910
he wants a map at 1 to 10,000.

00:33:25.910 --> 00:33:31.720
This is going to show you
buildings, trees in some cases

00:33:31.720 --> 00:33:35.870
with the Germans map,
particular trees, wells,

00:33:35.870 --> 00:33:37.760
very detailed information.

