The artillery want a little
bit of a bigger picture

00:33:41.310 --> 00:33:45.950
because they're shooting
miles down the road.

00:33:45.950 --> 00:33:49.500
And for planning, 1 to 40,000,
I'd give me a regional picture

00:33:49.500 --> 00:33:53.290
and then I'll translate that
information into the infantry

00:33:53.290 --> 00:33:55.690
and the artillery planning.

00:33:55.690 --> 00:33:57.830
It has to show topography.

00:33:57.830 --> 00:34:03.060
It has to show waterways,
roads, communication lines,

00:34:03.060 --> 00:34:08.760
of course buildings and
military information.

00:34:08.760 --> 00:34:12.830
And things, although we think,
"Oh, it's a static war --

00:34:12.830 --> 00:34:15.890
they're in trenches,"
what was going on in

00:34:15.890 --> 00:34:19.670
and around those trenches
was changing all the time.

00:34:19.670 --> 00:34:23.620
And so, that information needed
to be updated daily often.

00:34:23.620 --> 00:34:28.180
Even if nothing changed, that might
be a sign of something is going on.

00:34:28.180 --> 00:34:30.200
Why is nothing going
on on the German side?

00:34:30.200 --> 00:34:31.500
We don't see anything.

00:34:31.500 --> 00:34:36.410
Well, maybe they've taken some
guys across the way and moved them

00:34:36.410 --> 00:34:38.460
down the line because they
want to attack down the line.

00:34:38.460 --> 00:34:41.230
So that information
is also important.

00:34:44.020 --> 00:34:46.650
So here's a blowup of
that same tactical map,

00:34:46.650 --> 00:34:48.070
and it's a German map, by the way.

00:34:48.070 --> 00:34:54.670
And it's showing an
Allied trench line.

00:34:54.670 --> 00:34:58.620
They don't put their own
information on this map

00:34:58.620 --> 00:35:01.660
because this is given
to a junior officer.

00:35:01.660 --> 00:35:05.410
And if he's out in the field and
he's captured or he drops this

00:35:05.410 --> 00:35:07.590 position:56%
and they show their own trench line,

00:35:07.590 --> 00:35:10.450
that's given away intelligence
to the enemy.

00:35:10.450 --> 00:35:16.100 position:56%
So often, what the folks in the
field had was a one-sided depiction.

00:35:16.100 --> 00:35:20.920
So, we see here an Allied trench
line with these X's are here

00:35:20.920 --> 00:35:22.220
in red that I'm tracing along.

00:35:22.220 --> 00:35:24.680
That's barbed wire,
and there are many,

00:35:24.680 --> 00:35:28.250
many rows of barbed
wire to inhibit attack.

00:35:28.250 --> 00:35:32.110
You can't pass through barbed
wire unless you blast it

00:35:32.110 --> 00:35:35.520
with artillery -- it's
that thick and dense.

00:35:37.900 --> 00:35:44.750 position:56%
Over here, we have a legend that
explains the information on the map.

00:35:44.750 --> 00:35:47.890
So the Germans even
went down to the level

00:35:47.890 --> 00:35:50.930
of showing deciduous
verses evergreen trees.

00:35:50.930 --> 00:35:53.340
I mean, they plotted this stuff.

00:35:53.340 --> 00:35:55.720
It's amazing.

00:35:55.720 --> 00:35:59.470
I suppose -- we were joking
about that earlier, Peter and I.

00:35:59.470 --> 00:36:03.670
But I guess that matters if
you're operating in a time

00:36:03.670 --> 00:36:05.440
when there's leaves on
the tree verses not.

00:36:05.440 --> 00:36:09.080
Are your troops concealed
or are they not concealed?

00:36:09.080 --> 00:36:12.490
Town maps -- how to interpret that.

00:36:12.490 --> 00:36:20.720
How to interpret topography and
various structures on a map,

00:36:20.720 --> 00:36:25.070
because junior officers are
not necessarily map experts.

00:36:25.070 --> 00:36:29.020
You've got to lay this out in
a very literal and clear way

00:36:29.020 --> 00:36:35.430
so that somebody with a low level
of training can use it effectively.

00:36:38.820 --> 00:36:42.500
So maps, as we know,
operate with a grid.

00:36:42.500 --> 00:36:45.190
You see that on all these maps,
every sort of maybe not think

00:36:45.190 --> 00:36:47.480
about the intended purpose.

00:36:47.480 --> 00:36:55.240 position:56%
So it's about subdividing geographic
space and allowing one to point

00:36:55.240 --> 00:36:58.760
to a specific place on earth
and share that information

00:36:58.760 --> 00:37:00.630
in common with someone else.

00:37:00.630 --> 00:37:04.320
You don't want to say, "Dr.
Abear, take the platoon

00:37:04.320 --> 00:37:06.810
down the road and take the church."

00:37:06.810 --> 00:37:09.100
"What church are you
asking me to take?"

00:37:09.100 --> 00:37:10.840
Right? If I give you a set

00:37:10.840 --> 00:37:16.810
of coordinates then we can agree
upon where is it going to be.

00:37:16.810 --> 00:37:22.180
And so, the way these grids
worked is that there was one

00:37:22.180 --> 00:37:29.640
for the 40,000, which was used
for planning, and one of 10,000.

00:37:29.640 --> 00:37:37.710
And each one of these squares would
get divided into four sectors,

00:37:37.710 --> 00:37:42.350
and that it would get
sub-divided again into 10,

00:37:42.350 --> 00:37:46.280
so these are 50 yard squares here.

00:37:46.280 --> 00:37:52.050
So it allows immense precision when
talking about a geographic location

00:37:52.050 --> 00:37:55.600
that should be bombarded
or should be attacked.

00:37:59.610 --> 00:38:03.750
And the same holds true
for aerial photography.

00:38:03.750 --> 00:38:08.630
It operated on a grid system
and they were given the job

00:38:08.630 --> 00:38:13.670
of mapping a particular
lettered square.

00:38:13.670 --> 00:38:15.880
This map here is by the British.

00:38:15.880 --> 00:38:18.000
It's in Belgium, of Ypres.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:20.080
And I'm going to show
you, they were challenged

00:38:20.080 --> 00:38:23.290 position:56%
with mapping letter I -- right here.

00:38:32.320 --> 00:38:38.900
As you can see on the map here
showing the town in the river,

00:38:38.900 --> 00:38:44.660
and here is the aerial
photograph of this location.

00:38:44.660 --> 00:38:46.160
Amazingly accurate, right?

00:38:46.160 --> 00:38:52.670
And we're talking, this
is 1916-1917 flyover.

00:38:52.670 --> 00:38:58.250
And to make this happen, they
would go into enemy territory

00:38:58.250 --> 00:39:05.120
on a daily basis, flying at
altitudes 10,000 feet maybe,

00:39:05.120 --> 00:39:08.860
lower sometimes, to get
this kind of clarity.

00:39:08.860 --> 00:39:11.990
And that would put them in
range of any anti-aircraft.

00:39:11.990 --> 00:39:16.670
It was a very dangerous
business doing this.

00:39:16.670 --> 00:39:21.300
And they were asked to go over
every day because planners

00:39:21.300 --> 00:39:24.130
and analysts wanted to
see if there's any change

00:39:24.130 --> 00:39:28.070
in what you captured today,
and how can we compare

00:39:28.070 --> 00:39:30.900 position:56%
that to what's happened in the past.

00:39:30.900 --> 00:39:34.560
So we can either have an
indication that they plan to attack

00:39:34.560 --> 00:39:38.080
or if they want to recede
from a certain area.

00:39:38.080 --> 00:39:39.380
They want to know that.

00:39:39.380 --> 00:39:43.950
So, this stuff is happening
on a daily basis.

00:39:43.950 --> 00:39:48.720
And flying in World War I, by the
way, was a very dangerous business.

00:39:48.720 --> 00:39:52.980
Most people are killed on takeoff.

00:39:52.980 --> 00:39:57.110
These are wooden planes, and if the
engine failed, you're in a plane

00:39:57.110 --> 00:39:59.080
with a heavy camera and
another person who's going

00:39:59.080 --> 00:40:00.400
to take the pictures.

00:40:00.400 --> 00:40:03.850
And if you don't get enough
lift and you come down heavy,

00:40:03.850 --> 00:40:06.420
that's the end, generally speaking.

00:40:11.040 --> 00:40:14.180
So, what were they
taking photographs of?

00:40:14.180 --> 00:40:16.500
What are you supposed to be
looking for if you're an analyst?

00:40:16.500 --> 00:40:18.240
So I'm going to ask all of you.

00:40:18.240 --> 00:40:22.520
Like, say you're an analyst and
this gets returned from a flight,

00:40:22.520 --> 00:40:26.430
and they said, "Where is
the machine gun nest?"

00:40:26.430 --> 00:40:28.680
Now, we can't ask Paulette
because she has a background

00:40:28.680 --> 00:40:32.140 position:56%
in this stuff, so she doesn't count.

00:40:32.140 --> 00:40:35.460
But some of you, if you
were given this photograph,

00:40:35.460 --> 00:40:38.560
where's the machine gun nest?

00:40:42.120 --> 00:40:43.960
It's right here.

00:40:43.960 --> 00:40:49.450
See this round secular
running in pairs?

00:40:49.450 --> 00:40:52.370 position:56%
There is two actually in this mound.

00:40:52.370 --> 00:40:56.250
What they were taught to
look for were features

00:40:56.250 --> 00:40:58.530
that don't generally
occur in nature.

00:40:58.530 --> 00:41:00.270
And human beings have a tendency

00:41:00.270 --> 00:41:04.250
to build things logically,
geometrically.

00:41:04.250 --> 00:41:06.840
And when you look at the earth,
the earth doesn't form that way.

00:41:06.840 --> 00:41:12.040
In the human mind, it wants to
construct it in this fashion.

00:41:12.040 --> 00:41:17.380
So they're taught to look for
what the human would build.

00:41:17.380 --> 00:41:22.330
And so, right there is a machine
gun that's on a hill that commands

00:41:22.330 --> 00:41:24.730
over these trenches down here.

00:41:27.620 --> 00:41:29.880
And there's a lot more
enemy activity actually

00:41:29.880 --> 00:41:32.180
on this photograph.

00:41:36.230 --> 00:41:38.930
Up here is a headquarters.

00:41:41.450 --> 00:41:45.480
These buildings, they determined
prisoners were being kept in.

00:41:47.380 --> 00:41:50.080
They set up roadblocks here.

00:41:51.660 --> 00:41:57.250
So, this flyover intelligence
was very important

00:41:57.250 --> 00:42:01.540
to develop tactical knowledge
of what the enemy was doing

00:42:01.540 --> 00:42:04.070
and where he was situated.

00:42:06.730 --> 00:42:10.220
So the question becomes,
okay, you got a photograph.

00:42:10.220 --> 00:42:11.520
You know where it is.

00:42:11.520 --> 00:42:14.510
How do you get that to a map?

00:42:14.510 --> 00:42:15.810
There are no computers.

00:42:15.810 --> 00:42:17.110
There's no GPS.

00:42:17.110 --> 00:42:19.120
There is no cut and pasting.

00:42:19.120 --> 00:42:21.230
So the process is called
rectification,

00:42:21.230 --> 00:42:27.720 position:56%
meaning transferring the information
onto a map to have it lined

00:42:27.720 --> 00:42:29.600
up with the coordinates of the map.

00:42:29.600 --> 00:42:33.770
It was a very primitive
process, yet very effective.

00:42:33.770 --> 00:42:37.880
What mappers were taught
to do was find the point

00:42:37.880 --> 00:42:41.360
that you're interested in that
shows up on a photograph here.

00:42:41.360 --> 00:42:46.260
Alignment it with known points.

00:42:46.260 --> 00:42:49.990
And they would trace the
photograph using tracing paper.

00:42:49.990 --> 00:42:55.990 position:56%
And then, they would take that known
grid which I told you about earlier

00:42:55.990 --> 00:42:59.020
where the plane would fly
over, and they would layer

00:42:59.020 --> 00:43:05.180
that upon a topographic map and
they would draw that onto the map.

00:43:05.180 --> 00:43:09.800
And that's how intelligence would
get laid over onto existing maps.

00:43:11.960 --> 00:43:18.330 position:56%
It seems very basic and rudimentary,
but it was miles and miles ahead

00:43:18.330 --> 00:43:22.840
with the world had ever done before
in terms of military mapping.

00:43:26.330 --> 00:43:30.750
Now, eyes on the ground
also was still important

00:43:30.750 --> 00:43:33.500
for intelligence mapping
in World War I.

00:43:33.500 --> 00:43:38.940
This is a patrol map from the
Germans in the Saint-Mihiel sector

00:43:38.940 --> 00:43:43.970
where the Americans launched
our first American-led

00:43:43.970 --> 00:43:46.270
offensive campaign.

00:43:48.960 --> 00:43:54.310
All sides sent patrols out, usually
at dawn or dusk to use the cover

00:43:54.310 --> 00:43:58.830
of darkness, and to approach
-- go through no man's land --

00:43:58.830 --> 00:44:05.270
as quietly as possible, and to
take note of the enemy lines.

00:44:05.270 --> 00:44:07.570
What do you see?

00:44:09.350 --> 00:44:10.650
Are they cooking food?

00:44:10.650 --> 00:44:17.590
Do you see anything behind the
lines, like trucks or supplies

00:44:17.590 --> 00:44:19.060
that had been recently deposited?

00:44:19.060 --> 00:44:22.040
Do you see artillery?

00:44:22.040 --> 00:44:23.340
When did you see?

00:44:23.340 --> 00:44:25.050
How much did you say?

00:44:25.050 --> 00:44:31.800
Patrol leaders in both armies
were required to fill out reports

00:44:31.800 --> 00:44:34.970
about what they had
seen, when, and where.

00:44:34.970 --> 00:44:38.360
This information would be then
kicked back to their headquarters

00:44:38.360 --> 00:44:41.590
and also used to update maps.

00:44:46.280 --> 00:44:51.380
And if they could such a patrol,
they loved to grab a prisoner.

00:44:51.380 --> 00:44:54.760
Sometimes they grabbed a
sentry, who was unwilling.

00:44:54.760 --> 00:44:58.650 position:56%
Sometimes the guy on the other side,
you know, I mean, was giving himself

00:44:58.650 --> 00:45:02.480
up too quickly without a fight.

00:45:02.480 --> 00:45:08.380
And this here is an American map
that shows intelligence garnered

00:45:08.380 --> 00:45:11.500
from a prisoner about
the German lines.

00:45:14.020 --> 00:45:17.950
We have here showing machine guns.

00:45:19.520 --> 00:45:21.760
Prisoner told them -- Here's
the American line, by the way.

00:45:21.760 --> 00:45:24.440
Here's the German line, okay.

00:45:24.440 --> 00:45:28.170
The Germans often would move
machine guns up close to the line

00:45:28.170 --> 00:45:31.940
to harass the Americans
in their trench.

00:45:31.940 --> 00:45:36.490
Should anyone stick their head
up, they would unload a blast

00:45:36.490 --> 00:45:38.790
of machine-gun fire on them.

00:45:40.930 --> 00:45:44.670
It told about a German
observation balloon here.

00:45:44.670 --> 00:45:47.210
Although we had planes, balloons
were still very important

00:45:47.210 --> 00:45:52.450
and very effective, but it
was a terrible job to have

00:45:52.450 --> 00:45:56.730
because they were very visual
to the enemy and they would go

00:45:56.730 --> 00:45:58.310
after them whenever possible.

00:45:58.310 --> 00:46:01.090
And if you're in a balloon that
catches fire and is coming down,

00:46:01.090 --> 00:46:03.830
there's really no way out.

00:46:05.740 --> 00:46:08.040
Here the Germans have an airfield.

00:46:08.040 --> 00:46:12.390
And behind, deep in their
line, is their artillery,

00:46:12.390 --> 00:46:16.940
their heavy artillery, field
artillery, and their mortars.

00:46:16.940 --> 00:46:19.870
So this information from
prisoners is very valuable

00:46:19.870 --> 00:46:24.850
to get a better picture
of the enemy lines.

00:46:24.850 --> 00:46:29.420
Aerial photography couldn't always
get the stuff because you learn

00:46:29.420 --> 00:46:32.030
to camouflage, you learn
to adapt and overcome.

00:46:32.030 --> 00:46:35.170
The enemy is spying from above,
so they would throw netting

00:46:35.170 --> 00:46:40.720
or do various things to try to
deceive the aerial reconnaissance.

00:46:40.720 --> 00:46:45.620
And we see this sort of going
on today in the various wars

00:46:45.620 --> 00:46:54.280
in Afghanistan and elsewhere in the
Middle East, in northern Africa.

00:46:55.300 --> 00:47:00.690
United States and NATO has drones
and airplanes, heat detection.

00:47:00.690 --> 00:47:05.860
So, opposition elements are turning
towards tunnels, concealment.

00:47:05.860 --> 00:47:11.290
It's a cat and mouse game from the
beginning of warfare has occurred,

00:47:11.290 --> 00:47:13.590
and this is part of that.

00:47:16.550 --> 00:47:19.950
All of this information
would be used to culminate

00:47:19.950 --> 00:47:25.130
in something called "the
enemy order of battle."

00:47:25.130 --> 00:47:28.430
What does that mean?

00:47:28.430 --> 00:47:33.700
Ideally, you can identify
enemy units by their name.

00:47:33.700 --> 00:47:35.000
Who are they?

00:47:35.000 --> 00:47:37.730
What's their specialty?

00:47:37.730 --> 00:47:39.920 position:56%
What is the quality of those troops?

00:47:39.920 --> 00:47:41.220
Do they have experience?

00:47:41.220 --> 00:47:44.240
Are they very green?

00:47:44.240 --> 00:47:46.740
Also equally important is how
long have they been fighting?

00:47:46.740 --> 00:47:50.660
You know, if they're good
troops, good troops get tired.

00:47:50.660 --> 00:47:55.760
And the Germans -- because
I mentioned earlier,

00:47:55.760 --> 00:47:58.990
the Central Powers had less
manpower than the allies --

00:47:58.990 --> 00:48:01.900
they could not rotate
their men off the line.

00:48:01.900 --> 00:48:03.640
When you're on the line,
you stayed on the line.

00:48:03.640 --> 00:48:06.390
And individuals would
maybe go on leave,

00:48:06.390 --> 00:48:09.330
but groups of soldiers would not
be taken off the line together.

00:48:09.330 --> 00:48:10.800
The Allies had that luxury.

00:48:10.800 --> 00:48:12.460
They could take a whole unit off

00:48:12.460 --> 00:48:16.520
and put a whole new unit
on the line to rest.

00:48:16.520 --> 00:48:18.630
Also, when were they last in battle

00:48:18.630 --> 00:48:22.590
and what's their morale
and level of supply?

00:48:22.590 --> 00:48:27.660
If they have low morale
and they're not being fed,

00:48:27.660 --> 00:48:29.340
maybe that's where
you want to attack,

00:48:29.340 --> 00:48:32.650
because they're going
to maybe give up easier.

00:48:32.650 --> 00:48:36.530
And if you can create a hole in the
enemy line with one of these units

00:48:36.530 --> 00:48:38.610
that has low morale or low supply,

00:48:38.610 --> 00:48:44.010
you could compromise their
entire defense in a given area.

00:48:44.010 --> 00:48:46.290
And so, that opportunity was a kind

00:48:46.290 --> 00:48:49.640
of opportunity the planners
would look to exploit.

00:48:49.640 --> 00:48:53.550
And they would present this
information to commanding officers

00:48:53.550 --> 00:48:56.630
to make decisions about operations.

00:48:58.390 --> 00:49:01.210
The last map I'm going to mention

00:49:01.210 --> 00:49:04.000
of the military kind
here is a planning map.

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:09.210
This is a map from the
Meuse-Argonne, and these kind

00:49:09.210 --> 00:49:11.390
of maps have a particular look.

00:49:11.390 --> 00:49:15.390
They show something called
jumping off points here,

00:49:15.390 --> 00:49:18.060 position:56%
where units would begin in a battle.

00:49:18.060 --> 00:49:21.920
And they would follow a line
of progress, [inaudible] line.

00:49:21.920 --> 00:49:24.130
They were given a sector.

00:49:24.130 --> 00:49:26.190
"You stay in your lane
and I stay in my lane,

00:49:26.190 --> 00:49:28.240
and we move forward together,

00:49:28.240 --> 00:49:32.250
so that we don't get
salience in our line.

00:49:32.250 --> 00:49:35.310
We don't want to have one group
go forward, and a group next

00:49:35.310 --> 00:49:38.850
to it stays behind, because that
protruding salient then becomes

00:49:38.850 --> 00:49:41.500
vulnerable to attack on two sides.

00:49:41.500 --> 00:49:49.030
We want to move together along
the same axis of advance.

00:49:49.030 --> 00:49:51.550
And so, this is the beginning
of the Meuse-Argonne offensive,

00:49:51.550 --> 00:49:54.770
all the way up to November
11 on the armistice,

00:49:54.770 --> 00:49:58.260
where we pushed the Germans back.

00:50:03.040 --> 00:50:06.630
Now, I mentioned in the
beginning, weapons were important

00:50:06.630 --> 00:50:09.840
to [inaudible], and the greatest
weapon in the most effective weapon

00:50:09.840 --> 00:50:12.170
of the war was artillery,

00:50:12.170 --> 00:50:17.010
responsible for some 60 plus
percent of all casualties.

00:50:18.500 --> 00:50:22.530
These are some of the various guns
that the American army employed,

00:50:22.530 --> 00:50:26.630
from this field artillery
here to this railgun

00:50:26.630 --> 00:50:29.840
which could shoot some 20 miles.

00:50:29.840 --> 00:50:35.610
And it would lay waste
to the landscape.

00:50:35.610 --> 00:50:37.220
Forested areas would just turn

00:50:37.220 --> 00:50:42.780
into effectively something
looking like a lunar landscape.

00:50:42.780 --> 00:50:47.050
The amount of devastation that they
could deliver was incredible --

00:50:47.050 --> 00:50:50.710
incredible in a very
dark way, of course.

00:50:50.710 --> 00:50:55.570
What makes this possible are
maps to direct this fire.

00:50:55.570 --> 00:50:56.890
They're not just guessing.

00:50:56.890 --> 00:51:01.470
They're firing at known points.

00:51:01.470 --> 00:51:05.710
Towards the end of the war,
the mapping was so accurate

00:51:05.710 --> 00:51:10.890
that they felt that they could hit
something that had an air factor

00:51:10.890 --> 00:51:14.890
of maybe 50 to 20 yards of being
off if they just used a map

00:51:14.890 --> 00:51:18.160
with no pre-firing, where they
could see the round go down.

00:51:18.160 --> 00:51:20.370
And the spotter would call
back and say "Adjust."

00:51:20.370 --> 00:51:24.160
They felt that they had mapped
it effectively, they could shoot

00:51:24.160 --> 00:51:27.710
and surprise the enemy and
not give them a chance to move

00:51:27.710 --> 00:51:30.310
and hit the target, and
that's very incredible.

00:51:30.310 --> 00:51:31.610
This is all analog.

00:51:31.610 --> 00:51:35.090
There's no digital,
GPS guiding this stuff.

00:51:35.090 --> 00:51:39.020
Yeah, it was amazing --
again, in a very dark way.

00:51:39.020 --> 00:51:46.760
This map here comes from one
of our special collections,

00:51:46.760 --> 00:51:48.390
the John Heinz Collection,

00:51:48.390 --> 00:51:53.630
and it shows America's first
artillery shock of the war.

00:51:53.630 --> 00:51:57.500
It's kind of a neat specimen
to have in our archive here.

00:51:57.500 --> 00:52:02.960
On October 23, 1917 at
approximately 6:30 AM,

00:52:02.960 --> 00:52:08.590
Battery C of the six field
regiment, first field brigade,

00:52:08.590 --> 00:52:12.530
first division -- have to get it
all in -- under Colonel Scott,

00:52:12.530 --> 00:52:16.090 position:56%
Major Starkey, and Captain McLendon,

00:52:16.090 --> 00:52:20.640
said to Sergeant Alexander
Arch, "Go ahead and shoot."

00:52:20.640 --> 00:52:26.730
And Aches' battery is here,
and they take the first shot

00:52:26.730 --> 00:52:29.920
against the Germans in anger.

00:52:29.920 --> 00:52:33.220
General Pershing said,
"That's a special gun."

00:52:33.220 --> 00:52:38.490
Pershing is the commander-in-chief
of the American forces.

00:52:38.490 --> 00:52:44.450
He said, "Send that gun home,"
and that gun is in West Point now.

00:52:44.450 --> 00:52:48.750 position:56%
And the gun, incidentally, is French
make, 75 millimeter field gun.

00:52:48.750 --> 00:52:55.130
The United States Army, at
the time of World War I,

00:52:55.130 --> 00:52:57.900
did not have a lot
of heavy ordinance.

00:52:57.900 --> 00:53:02.290
We were able to bring
bodies to Europe,

00:53:02.290 --> 00:53:04.620
but not necessarily
the gear to go with it.

00:53:04.620 --> 00:53:09.750
We had to use British and
French equipment to fight.

00:53:09.750 --> 00:53:11.400
This is very different
in World War I,

00:53:11.400 --> 00:53:16.240
where we're supplying all the
Allies with various armaments,

00:53:16.240 --> 00:53:20.830
like the British with
Sherman tanks and the Russians

00:53:20.830 --> 00:53:22.960
with trucks, for example.

00:53:22.960 --> 00:53:26.710
So this is a very interesting
piece of history right here

00:53:26.710 --> 00:53:30.000
from the Library of
Congress' collections.

00:53:32.570 --> 00:53:35.130
One tactic that made artillery

00:53:35.130 --> 00:53:39.210
so devastating was something
called creeping barrage,

00:53:39.210 --> 00:53:47.070
something developed by the British
in the Boer Wars of South Africa.

00:53:47.070 --> 00:53:53.000
Creeping barrage meant we want to
put the artillery fire in front

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:57.260
of our troops, and have that fire
move forward while our troops move

00:53:57.260 --> 00:54:00.110
behind it to limit
the enemy's ability

00:54:00.110 --> 00:54:03.250
to shoot our troops advancing.

00:54:03.250 --> 00:54:07.700
In order to pull off this complex
maneuver, two things are important.

00:54:07.700 --> 00:54:10.520
You got to both know
where you're going to be,

00:54:10.520 --> 00:54:15.630 position:56%
because you don't want the guys here
when the bombs are falling here.

00:54:15.630 --> 00:54:18.480
They want to be behind
these various rings of fire,

00:54:18.480 --> 00:54:20.420
"curtain of fire" they called it,

00:54:20.420 --> 00:54:22.530
and what time that
that would happen.

00:54:22.530 --> 00:54:25.720
So the artillery unit and the unit

00:54:25.720 --> 00:54:30.760
in the field would share the same
map, and according to a schedule,

00:54:30.760 --> 00:54:32.060
they would move together.

00:54:32.060 --> 00:54:37.550
And this was very effective
at blasting away barbed wire

00:54:37.550 --> 00:54:41.280
and other enemy emplacements
along the way,

00:54:41.280 --> 00:54:45.020
to reach the final objective where
then the infantry could charge

00:54:45.020 --> 00:54:48.970
into the enemy trench
and take it over.

00:54:48.970 --> 00:54:53.050
This particular map also
has a unique history.

00:54:53.050 --> 00:54:59.270
It's from the G and M Collection
by General Charles Summerall.

00:54:59.270 --> 00:55:04.920
Summerall ordered an
attack on November 10, 1918.

00:55:04.920 --> 00:55:07.770
Does that sound significant to you?

00:55:07.770 --> 00:55:09.950
Because November 11 is the day

00:55:09.950 --> 00:55:12.690
that the armistice is
going to take place.

00:55:12.690 --> 00:55:15.860
He ordered an attack,
because he was of the mind

00:55:15.860 --> 00:55:20.700
that the Germans were faking,
that this armistice was baloney.

00:55:20.700 --> 00:55:25.550
They just wanted time to rest
and recover, and that we needed

00:55:25.550 --> 00:55:27.070
to keep the heat on them.

00:55:27.070 --> 00:55:33.710
So he orders troops to
cross the Meuse River

00:55:33.710 --> 00:55:37.360
and to take German
positions on the other side.

00:55:37.360 --> 00:55:41.930
In this attack, some
360 plus Marines --

00:55:41.930 --> 00:55:45.440 position:56%
not part of the Army but under their
command and some of the best troops

00:55:45.440 --> 00:55:49.970
that we had at the time -- die.

00:55:49.970 --> 00:55:52.830
It becomes a scandal
back in Washington.

00:55:52.830 --> 00:55:57.840
Why did you send Marines
across a river

00:55:57.840 --> 00:56:00.680
where the Germans had machine
guns on the other side,

00:56:00.680 --> 00:56:06.100
to die on the next-to-last
day of the war?

00:56:06.100 --> 00:56:10.800 position:56%
Pershing and other military
leaders came to Summerall's defense.

00:56:10.800 --> 00:56:13.910
They said, "We didn't know if
the Germans were going to give up

00:56:13.910 --> 00:56:17.520
or not, and we had to
keep the heat on them."

00:56:17.520 --> 00:56:22.800 position:56%
And Summerall was exonerated for any
wrongdoing, although the families

00:56:22.800 --> 00:56:28.060
of the servicemen who died hated
him tremendously for this order.

00:56:29.690 --> 00:56:32.290
And this, again, is part of
the Summerall papers in the G

00:56:32.290 --> 00:56:34.970
and M Collection that any
one of you want to come in

00:56:34.970 --> 00:56:37.270
and review, it's available.

00:56:41.200 --> 00:56:45.770
Since artillery was so
dangerous, it's important

00:56:45.770 --> 00:56:47.870
to locate the enemy's artillery,

00:56:47.870 --> 00:56:50.740
and I talked about aerial
photography was one means,

00:56:50.740 --> 00:56:52.890
patrol was the other.

00:56:52.890 --> 00:56:56.790
But often, those methodologies
were insufficient to map

00:56:56.790 --> 00:57:00.800
where the enemy's artillery
might in fact be.

00:57:00.800 --> 00:57:04.360
Both sides develop something
called "sound ranging,"

00:57:04.360 --> 00:57:07.240
and the technologies among
the different armies varied

00:57:07.240 --> 00:57:10.100
and I'm going to generalize
what they did here.

00:57:10.100 --> 00:57:14.960
This map by the U.S.
Army, using sound ranging

00:57:14.960 --> 00:57:21.360
to detect German batteries
across the front lines.

00:57:22.410 --> 00:57:27.240
Microphones would be set
up along predefined points.

00:57:27.240 --> 00:57:29.950
And when a gun would fire,
the sound would travel

00:57:29.950 --> 00:57:35.130
and reach those microphones
at different times.

00:57:35.130 --> 00:57:38.720
They would calculate how long the
sound took to reach the vibration,

00:57:38.720 --> 00:57:44.580
to reach the microphone, and
triangulate where the gun might be.

00:57:44.580 --> 00:57:47.880
This was so effective that they
could triangulate an enemy gun

00:57:47.880 --> 00:57:50.780
within about 20 yards
by the end of the war.

00:57:50.780 --> 00:57:56.490
So what that meant was that if you
shoot, you got to move your gun.

00:57:56.490 --> 00:58:00.340
If you got to move your gun, that
means you're exposing your gun

00:58:00.340 --> 00:58:05.330
to reconnaissance, so
you better make it count.

00:58:05.330 --> 00:58:07.780
So this but the Germans, in
particular, in a predicament

00:58:07.780 --> 00:58:09.470
because when they would shoot,

00:58:09.470 --> 00:58:13.080
we would fire a counter
battery barrage right away

00:58:13.080 --> 00:58:14.990
to blast their guns.

00:58:14.990 --> 00:58:17.410
They would try to move the
guns to a new hiding place.

00:58:17.410 --> 00:58:20.650
We would immediately send up
airplanes and look for them,

00:58:20.650 --> 00:58:23.810
and we were hot on their
tail and they knew it.

00:58:28.310 --> 00:58:34.460
So trenches, of course, then, it
should be stated, is more important

00:58:34.460 --> 00:58:37.490
because artillery was
so devastating.

00:58:37.490 --> 00:58:39.690
Where could you safely put
troops then on the front line

00:58:39.690 --> 00:58:41.270
if these maps were so accurate,

00:58:41.270 --> 00:58:44.640
and 60% of all casualties
are caused by big guns.

00:58:44.640 --> 00:58:47.140
How do we keep the troops safe?

00:58:47.140 --> 00:58:48.440
And it was the trench.

00:58:48.440 --> 00:58:50.930
The trench was -- we think
of it as a terrible place.

00:58:50.930 --> 00:58:53.960
It's muddy, it's dirty,
it's got rats,

00:58:53.960 --> 00:58:56.340
all kind of disease
in these trenches.

00:58:56.340 --> 00:58:58.010
Who wants to be in a trench?

00:58:58.010 --> 00:59:03.350
But on a World War I battlefield,
the trench, generally speaking,

00:59:03.350 --> 00:59:05.250
is the safest place to be.

00:59:05.250 --> 00:59:09.330
The problem with the
trench is getting out of it.

00:59:09.330 --> 00:59:11.910
And when they blow the whistle
and they say you've got to go

00:59:11.910 --> 00:59:18.270
over the top to attack the enemy,
men were mowed down within feet

00:59:18.270 --> 00:59:22.350
of their own trench line, because
the enemy had it pre-sited,

00:59:22.350 --> 00:59:24.780
meaning they knew where
you would come out.

00:59:24.780 --> 00:59:28.020
There were snipers, machine
guns, their artillery,

00:59:28.020 --> 00:59:30.970
and they were ready to blast away.

00:59:34.540 --> 00:59:36.850
This map here is what
we call a trench map.

00:59:36.850 --> 00:59:38.150
It's a German trench map.

00:59:38.150 --> 00:59:42.650
We have British, American, and
many other versions of trench maps

00:59:42.650 --> 00:59:46.770
in the collections of
the Library of Congress.

00:59:46.770 --> 00:59:52.650 position:56%
Trenches of World War I often were
organized what they call "in depth,"

00:59:52.650 --> 00:59:57.160
meaning there was a main line
of defense, a secondary line,

00:59:57.160 --> 00:59:59.550
and finally a third line.

01:00:00.760 --> 01:00:04.120
The idea here was that
that the enemy attack.

01:00:04.120 --> 01:00:08.530
We have light forces in
the front to screen them.

01:00:08.530 --> 01:00:12.890
Should we need to, we would
fall back to the second line.

01:00:14.110 --> 01:00:18.460
The advantage of this is
they sent men over the top.

01:00:18.460 --> 01:00:20.180
They had taken this position.

01:00:20.180 --> 01:00:21.480
We fall back here.

01:00:21.480 --> 01:00:23.850
Our artillery is back here.

01:00:23.850 --> 01:00:28.570
We have this all mapped out
very nicely, and we're happy

01:00:28.570 --> 01:00:31.760
to blast our own front
line trench to bits,

01:00:31.760 --> 01:00:33.100
now that the enemy has occupied it.

01:00:33.100 --> 01:00:35.950
And this was a trick that
the Germans would use.

01:00:35.950 --> 01:00:39.950
And the Americans, because
we entered the war in 1917,

01:00:39.950 --> 01:00:41.880
we were a little bit
slow to pick up on this,

01:00:41.880 --> 01:00:44.800
although our Allies
warned us about it.

01:00:44.800 --> 01:00:47.670
And we would occupy
their trenches and stay.

01:00:47.670 --> 01:00:52.630
And the French were like, "You
need to keep going forward."

01:00:52.630 --> 01:00:56.110
And after a few blasts -- and
this happened a few times --

01:00:56.110 --> 01:00:59.470
our commanders adjusted
and said, "You can't stay.

01:00:59.470 --> 01:01:04.140
You need to move to the
second line and to safety."

01:01:05.540 --> 01:01:11.280
Incidentally, this map is
from the area of Verdun,

01:01:11.280 --> 01:01:14.620
an important battlefield
of World War I.

01:01:14.620 --> 01:01:19.320
Verdun was a very political battle.

01:01:19.320 --> 01:01:23.030
The Germans said in 1916 when
they were unable to take France

01:01:23.030 --> 01:01:27.830
by mobile warfare, that
they would wear the Allies

01:01:27.830 --> 01:01:29.130
out through attrition.

01:01:29.130 --> 01:01:32.380
And they said, "The French
will defend a very historical

01:01:32.380 --> 01:01:37.440
and sacred city of Verdun with
as many troops as it takes.

01:01:37.440 --> 01:01:40.710
So we will force them
into this cauldron

01:01:40.710 --> 01:01:43.170
and kill as many as possible."

01:01:43.170 --> 01:01:47.910
And the German field
commanders were appalled

01:01:47.910 --> 01:01:52.820 position:56%
by this high command decision
because they said, "You're asking me

01:01:52.820 --> 01:01:57.670
to order my men to fight,
not to gain an objective

01:01:57.670 --> 01:02:00.020
or ground -- something tangible.

01:02:00.020 --> 01:02:02.530
You're asking my men
just to go out and fight

01:02:02.530 --> 01:02:05.330
and kill until they get killed.

01:02:05.330 --> 01:02:08.980
How can we sustain this?"

01:02:08.980 --> 01:02:11.550
Whereas on the French side, they
said, "This is our territory.

01:02:11.550 --> 01:02:12.850
This is our land."

01:02:12.850 --> 01:02:15.230
It became a sacred battle
for the honor of France,

01:02:15.230 --> 01:02:19.360
and they staved off the
German offensive here.

01:02:19.360 --> 01:02:24.130
And it was a high cost
of life to both sides.

01:02:24.130 --> 01:02:28.820
The ground was virtually just
stagnant -- the trench lines.

01:02:33.150 --> 01:02:36.250
One of the last maps I want
to show you of the war here is

01:02:36.250 --> 01:02:40.970
of the armistice, 11/11/1918.

01:02:44.410 --> 01:02:50.540
This map was initially a secret
map showing the final disposition

01:02:50.540 --> 01:02:56.280
of forces as they would stand
when the armistice was to begin.

01:02:56.280 --> 01:03:01.800
The Allies had in the field at
this time some 280 plus divisions

01:03:01.800 --> 01:03:07.510
that were well fed, rested,
high morale, good supplies.

01:03:07.510 --> 01:03:11.730
The Germans had 180
under-strength divisions.

01:03:11.730 --> 01:03:13.240
They were called division on paper,

01:03:13.240 --> 01:03:16.930
but maybe they were half
strength, even less.

01:03:16.930 --> 01:03:18.560
They weren't getting food.

01:03:18.560 --> 01:03:20.510
Their guns were being worn out.

01:03:20.510 --> 01:03:24.310
The barrels were so worn that
they couldn't shoot straight.

01:03:24.310 --> 01:03:32.040
They realized that the Americans
have now come into the war in 1970

01:03:32.040 --> 01:03:33.550
and advancing against us.

01:03:33.550 --> 01:03:36.830
And Americans, incidentally,
put some 2 million troops

01:03:36.830 --> 01:03:38.800
into battle against the Germans.

01:03:38.800 --> 01:03:40.100
It was just too much.

01:03:40.100 --> 01:03:42.750
They were tired, fighting
since 1914.

01:03:42.750 --> 01:03:46.410
The Americans come along,
very fresh, energized.

01:03:46.410 --> 01:03:47.900
They bring this new momentum.

01:03:47.900 --> 01:03:51.260
The Allies start the hundred days
campaign against the Germans,

01:03:51.260 --> 01:03:55.610
and it culminates with
this armistice on the 11th.

01:03:59.220 --> 01:04:06.420
So Germany before this happened,
wanted to look for a way out.

01:04:06.420 --> 01:04:09.100
They said, "What can we do

01:04:09.100 --> 01:04:11.450
to preserve what we
have taken in this war?"

01:04:11.450 --> 01:04:14.560 position:56%
And I know I've been focusing on the
Western front, but I want to bring

01:04:14.560 --> 01:04:18.450
in a map from the Eastern
front because it is important

01:04:18.450 --> 01:04:21.790
to understand the German
psychology at the time,

01:04:21.790 --> 01:04:24.410
and then leading to World War II.

01:04:24.410 --> 01:04:32.160
So the map here, this says,
"Our march in the East.

01:04:32.160 --> 01:04:35.540
The facts versus the lies."

01:04:35.540 --> 01:04:40.920
The Germans took all this
territory on the Eastern front

01:04:40.920 --> 01:04:42.270
from the Russians in this area

01:04:42.270 --> 01:04:46.420
that eventually would
become Poland, okay.

01:04:46.420 --> 01:04:49.930
They were hugely successful
against the Russians.

01:04:51.600 --> 01:04:56.750
And in fact, the allowed
Lenin who was in Switzerland,

01:04:56.750 --> 01:04:59.220
passage to Germany into Russia.

01:04:59.220 --> 01:05:03.760
And they gave him money
with the thought being

01:05:03.760 --> 01:05:09.430
that this guy is crazy enough
to bring followers to his side

01:05:09.430 --> 01:05:12.430
and to get the Russians
out of the war.

01:05:12.430 --> 01:05:14.220
And he was successful.

01:05:14.220 --> 01:05:16.290
The Russians had sent
millions to their deaths

01:05:16.290 --> 01:05:18.300
on the front lines,
lives of casualties.

01:05:18.300 --> 01:05:19.600
They didn't want to fight anymore.

01:05:19.600 --> 01:05:20.900
There were tired.

01:05:20.900 --> 01:05:22.360
The Communists took control.

01:05:22.360 --> 01:05:25.060
They negotiated a peace
with the Germans,

01:05:25.060 --> 01:05:27.660
and the Germans took all
this land, the Baltics,

01:05:27.660 --> 01:05:30.450
Ukraine, all this, Poland.

01:05:30.450 --> 01:05:33.700
This was all the German
Empire in the East.

01:05:33.700 --> 01:05:36.350
And we see that here
also on this map printed

01:05:36.350 --> 01:05:39.390
by the United States Committee
of Public Information.

01:05:39.390 --> 01:05:40.690
See all this territory?

01:05:40.690 --> 01:05:42.820
The pink is the land
which the Germans

01:05:42.820 --> 01:05:46.420
and the Austro-Hungarians
extended their empires,

01:05:46.420 --> 01:05:48.550
Belgium, portions of France.

01:05:48.550 --> 01:05:49.960
This was in 1917.

01:05:49.960 --> 01:05:56.620
And the Germans say at this point
in time, they start talking,

01:05:56.620 --> 01:05:58.810
"Let's settle this, Woodrow Wilson.

01:05:58.810 --> 01:06:04.320
You're the great negotiator
for peace.

01:06:04.320 --> 01:06:06.980
You want us to sit down
and talk about this?

01:06:06.980 --> 01:06:08.820
We're happy to end the war now.

01:06:08.820 --> 01:06:14.130
Because the Germans realized,
"We can't push them away.

01:06:14.130 --> 01:06:15.920
We've tried our best.

01:06:15.920 --> 01:06:17.220
What can we do?

01:06:17.220 --> 01:06:18.580
So let's negotiate."

01:06:18.580 --> 01:06:22.460
But the Germans had
infuriated the United States.

01:06:22.460 --> 01:06:25.180
As you know, they sunk
the Lusitania.

01:06:25.180 --> 01:06:29.240
They were sinking other ships
of ours, acts of sabotage

01:06:29.240 --> 01:06:36.080
within the United States such as
blowing up the ammunition depot

01:06:36.080 --> 01:06:39.590
at Black Tom Island in New Jersey.

01:06:39.590 --> 01:06:44.060
Up here in Baltimore, there
is a place called Hansa Haus.

01:06:44.060 --> 01:06:49.560
It still exists, and the
Germans had a legation there.

01:06:49.560 --> 01:06:55.110
They brought in spies by submarine
to recruit German-Americans

01:06:55.110 --> 01:06:59.120
to engage in acts of
spying and sabotage.

01:07:00.210 --> 01:07:03.680
And then, they tried this plan
called the Zimmerman Telegram

01:07:03.680 --> 01:07:07.530 position:56%
which you may have heard about,
where they wanted to enlist the help

01:07:07.530 --> 01:07:10.210
of Mexico to occupy
the United States

01:07:10.210 --> 01:07:12.910
so it wouldn't come to Europe.

01:07:12.910 --> 01:07:15.720
All this had come to the attention
of the American leadership,

01:07:15.720 --> 01:07:21.070
