do what the British do best,

01:23:14.040 --> 01:23:19.960 position:56%
which is threaten the city there and
hope that they would be defeated.

01:23:19.960 --> 01:23:21.260
Ships were sunk.

01:23:21.260 --> 01:23:22.560
Men were lost.

01:23:22.560 --> 01:23:27.100 position:56%
The Navy turned back, and it was
relied upon for boots on the ground.

01:23:27.100 --> 01:23:29.070
You can imagine when I
give this at West Point,

01:23:29.070 --> 01:23:31.510
that's where I get the
biggest cheer -- for that.

01:23:31.510 --> 01:23:34.410
[ Laughter ]

01:23:34.410 --> 01:23:36.380
So, the Navy withdrew.

01:23:36.380 --> 01:23:39.240
The Army has to come --
the Army and the Marines.

01:23:39.240 --> 01:23:43.450
And landings therefore on a hostile
shore would then be necessary.

01:23:43.450 --> 01:23:47.660
And if you look at any of the
doctrines of amphibious landing,

01:23:47.660 --> 01:23:51.720
landing on a hostile shore is
of the most difficult order.

01:23:51.720 --> 01:23:56.180
So it was a gamble.

01:23:56.180 --> 01:23:58.410
This look at this gamble.

01:23:58.410 --> 01:24:02.730
Here, we can see the peculiar
shape of the Gallipoli Peninsula.

01:24:02.730 --> 01:24:05.070
We can see the narrowness
of the Dardanelle Straits

01:24:05.070 --> 01:24:08.070
and we can see its location
there in Turkey, in Europe.

01:24:08.070 --> 01:24:13.430
Turkey had been shrinking in size
because of various Balkan wars.

01:24:13.430 --> 01:24:17.290
The landings weren't there to
actually just take the Peninsula.

01:24:17.290 --> 01:24:23.160
The landings were there to silence
the guns and remove the minefields

01:24:23.160 --> 01:24:26.140
to allow the Navy to do its job.

01:24:26.140 --> 01:24:29.730
So they were actually
supporting the Navy.

01:24:29.730 --> 01:24:32.710
There were some possible
landing places.

01:24:32.710 --> 01:24:35.050
These lending places had
been surveyed already.

01:24:35.050 --> 01:24:39.260
They had been in place since
the early 19th century.

01:24:39.260 --> 01:24:43.830
At this location here to the
neck of the peninsula Bulair,

01:24:43.830 --> 01:24:46.250
ironically this was
a fortified zone,

01:24:46.250 --> 01:24:50.390
fortified by the Anglo-French
Army during the Crimean War,

01:24:50.390 --> 01:24:56.300
when the Ottoman Turks were allies
to the French and the British.

01:24:56.300 --> 01:24:58.540
There was also the
possibility of landing

01:24:58.540 --> 01:25:00.900
on the Asiatic shore,
as it was called.

01:25:00.900 --> 01:25:05.550
Remember, this is the junction of
two continents, Asia and Europe.

01:25:05.550 --> 01:25:07.560
So, there's a possibility
of landing there.

01:25:07.560 --> 01:25:09.950
But if you land there, you're
going to get lots and lots

01:25:09.950 --> 01:25:14.050
of angry Turks on your
back, in effect.

01:25:14.050 --> 01:25:19.390
And so, remaining are these
beaches here across the peninsula,

01:25:19.390 --> 01:25:24.180
both at the point here at Cape
Helles to this location here

01:25:24.180 --> 01:25:28.840
at Gaba Tepe, or here, an
unknown place in Suvla Bay.

01:25:28.840 --> 01:25:31.920
All of those things, landing
places had been surveyed

01:25:31.920 --> 01:25:33.780
and were in position.

01:25:33.780 --> 01:25:40.330
And by April 25, 1915,
just under a month

01:25:40.330 --> 01:25:45.650
after the Naval attempt had
failed, the British, French,

01:25:45.650 --> 01:25:48.110
and Australians landed here.

01:25:48.110 --> 01:25:50.640
Did you know the French
were at Gallipoli?

01:25:50.640 --> 01:25:52.920
No? One thing, just the one thing.

01:25:52.920 --> 01:25:59.330
So we can see Anzac -- Australian
and New Zealand Army Corps --

01:25:59.330 --> 01:26:03.370
the British 29th division --
a strange echo, if you like,

01:26:03.370 --> 01:26:05.840 position:56%
of the 29th division at Omaha Beach.

01:26:05.840 --> 01:26:08.470
There are comparable issues there.

01:26:08.470 --> 01:26:11.880
And the French Corps de
Orient landing there to take

01:26:11.880 --> 01:26:14.970
on the Gallipoli Peninsula.

01:26:16.090 --> 01:26:18.960
Now, one thing that we have that
they didn't have was any kind

01:26:18.960 --> 01:26:21.420
of satellite imagery, obviously.

01:26:21.420 --> 01:26:25.930
What we can see from this satellite
image is a very peculiarity

01:26:25.930 --> 01:26:30.870
of this landscape, the challenge
of the geography of Gallipoli.

01:26:30.870 --> 01:26:32.940
Well, first and foremost, you
have the distance you have

01:26:32.940 --> 01:26:34.240
to travel in a straight line.

01:26:34.240 --> 01:26:38.300
It's 230 miles from the
entrance to the Dardanelles

01:26:38.300 --> 01:26:41.690
to Istanbul (Constantinople).

01:26:41.690 --> 01:26:45.650 position:56%
But getting there means jinking your
way through here and a long way,

01:26:45.650 --> 01:26:50.970
and you can see the offset and all
the strange coastline of Gallipoli.

01:26:50.970 --> 01:26:54.470
That's because we have the
junction of two tectonic plates,

01:26:54.470 --> 01:26:56.210
and therefore lots
and lots of breaks

01:26:56.210 --> 01:27:00.400
which have created this
parallel coastline and fractures.

01:27:00.400 --> 01:27:04.400 position:56%
So we can see how we get these
lines of fractures which are picking

01:27:04.400 --> 01:27:07.760
out for us the landscape
of Gallipoli.

01:27:07.760 --> 01:27:11.600
That was going to cause real
problems for the British

01:27:11.600 --> 01:27:14.660
and Anzac troops and
French who landed there.

01:27:15.860 --> 01:27:19.130
It also means that we have a rugged
terrain because as the faults

01:27:19.130 --> 01:27:22.970
and fractures operate, so
they uplift the landscape.

01:27:22.970 --> 01:27:27.510 position:56%
So just like the bad land topography
that we have in your Southwest,

01:27:27.510 --> 01:27:30.270
similar kind of situations
and uplifting landscape

01:27:30.270 --> 01:27:32.460
and down cutting, we
have exactly the same

01:27:32.460 --> 01:27:36.490
in miniature here in Gallipoli.

01:27:36.490 --> 01:27:40.370
And so, understanding this terrain
was essential to military success.

01:27:40.370 --> 01:27:42.950
If you look at the doctrine
of amphibious landing

01:27:42.950 --> 01:27:44.920
from your own United
States military,

01:27:44.920 --> 01:27:49.390
you will see that that is written
large in understanding that.

01:27:49.390 --> 01:27:51.780
Because those men, with
their boots on the ground,

01:27:51.780 --> 01:27:54.130
have to fight not only
against the enemy

01:27:54.130 --> 01:27:56.000
but also against the topography.

01:27:56.000 --> 01:28:00.140
And how are they going to know
what the topography is about?

01:28:00.140 --> 01:28:03.550
Well, they do that through maps.

01:28:03.550 --> 01:28:07.590
So, this is where the
map myth comes in.

01:28:07.590 --> 01:28:11.630
Here we have General Sir Ian
Hamilton, ramrod straight

01:28:11.630 --> 01:28:15.720
as you can see in typical
British fashion.

01:28:15.720 --> 01:28:17.490
He was the most senior general

01:28:17.490 --> 01:28:19.910
that was not directly
employed at that time.

01:28:19.910 --> 01:28:25.260
In Kitchener, who was Secretary of
State for War, was his superior.

01:28:25.260 --> 01:28:28.240
Hamilton looked up to
Kitchener and a great way.

01:28:28.240 --> 01:28:31.230
Kitchener was a man
who took no fools

01:28:31.230 --> 01:28:34.850
and listened to no kind of excuses.

01:28:34.850 --> 01:28:37.050
Yet, Hamilton made those excuses.

01:28:37.050 --> 01:28:39.490
Hamilton was put in charge
of the Gallipoli campaign.

01:28:39.490 --> 01:28:40.790
He was really experienced.

01:28:40.790 --> 01:28:43.140
He fought in the Anglo Boer
War, and yet he wrote --

01:28:43.140 --> 01:28:48.770
he was a very literary general --
he wrote after the war these words.

01:28:48.770 --> 01:28:53.250
"Ten long years of General Staff
created after the Boer war.

01:28:53.250 --> 01:28:56.880
Where are your plans for
an amphibious landing?"

01:28:56.880 --> 01:28:59.180
None, he is saying.

01:28:59.180 --> 01:29:02.450
"And it may have well been
the moon that I'm invading

01:29:02.450 --> 01:29:05.680
because I just don't
have any information."

01:29:05.680 --> 01:29:09.830
Now, one has to ask
oneself, is this true?

01:29:09.830 --> 01:29:11.390
Written in 1920.

01:29:11.390 --> 01:29:15.190
Remember that after the failure
of the Dardanelles of Gallipoli,

01:29:15.190 --> 01:29:22.180
Hamilton's career, esteemed and
distinguished, was in tatters.

01:29:22.180 --> 01:29:24.640
What we do know is
what he has written

01:29:24.640 --> 01:29:28.560
down about how he was
instructed to invade.

01:29:28.560 --> 01:29:32.610
The problem is, who is it
that's writing about this?

01:29:32.610 --> 01:29:33.930
So we can see here,

01:29:33.930 --> 01:29:39.150
Brigadier-General Aspinall-Oglander
was a colonel,

01:29:39.150 --> 01:29:43.920
senior staff officer,
with Hamilton in 1915.

01:29:43.920 --> 01:29:47.210
And so, when he's writing here,
he's defending his old chief.

01:29:47.210 --> 01:29:49.770
And what he's saying is that
Hamilton, when he was briefed

01:29:49.770 --> 01:29:53.530
by Kitchener, very, very brief

01:29:53.530 --> 01:29:57.600
because Kitchener didn't mince
words, he got some instructions.

01:29:57.600 --> 01:30:00.400
In essence, go and
take the Dardanelles.

01:30:00.400 --> 01:30:03.540
A handbook of the Army
-- Well, that's okay.

01:30:03.540 --> 01:30:05.540
That's only a couple
of years out of date.

01:30:05.540 --> 01:30:07.740
Everything like this will
ultimately be out of date.

01:30:07.740 --> 01:30:11.020
But two other elements
-- a prewar report

01:30:11.020 --> 01:30:14.930
of the Dardanelles defenses kind of
implying that it was substandard,

01:30:14.930 --> 01:30:19.360
and a map which is specifically
considered to be inaccurate.

01:30:19.360 --> 01:30:24.950 position:56%
In other words, their setting up the
mythology that the map is at fault,

01:30:24.950 --> 01:30:30.890
trying to hide perhaps that
Hamilton might have been at fault.

01:30:30.890 --> 01:30:34.340
So, what did they actually get?

01:30:34.340 --> 01:30:40.420
Well, we have the War Office
Handbooks that were provided.

01:30:40.420 --> 01:30:46.870
But we also have a whole range of
other reports, 1905, 1909, 1908.

01:30:46.870 --> 01:30:49.140
All of these things
had been prepared

01:30:49.140 --> 01:30:53.500
because Britain was cautious
about the Ottoman Empire.

01:30:53.500 --> 01:30:56.950
Remember that Great
Britain was involved in many

01:30:56.950 --> 01:30:59.260
of the Middle Eastern
states and Egypt

01:30:59.260 --> 01:31:01.920
in particular with the Suez Canal.

01:31:01.920 --> 01:31:06.070
Oh, and there was that map, the
map which creates the mythology.

01:31:06.070 --> 01:31:14.670
This map of two sheets of 1 inch to
1 mile map, 1 to 63,360 scale map.

01:31:16.020 --> 01:31:20.590
So, the corrective
to this is one man,

01:31:20.590 --> 01:31:22.950
another general, General Callwell.

01:31:22.950 --> 01:31:26.950
Callwell, cautious in
his British speech,

01:31:26.950 --> 01:31:30.920
director of military operations
in the British War Office,

01:31:30.920 --> 01:31:33.670
and a man who had been
involved in military planning

01:31:33.670 --> 01:31:36.070
and had actually been
involved in the preparation

01:31:36.070 --> 01:31:41.390
of those military reports in the
early part of the 20th century.

01:31:41.390 --> 01:31:46.230
So, if we try and unpack this,
Hamilton had been informed

01:31:46.230 --> 01:31:49.620
with information as to the
various possible landing points.

01:31:49.620 --> 01:31:53.000
He's saying Hamilton knew
about this information

01:31:53.000 --> 01:31:55.820
which was fairly correct
information,

01:31:55.820 --> 01:31:58.510
and that fairly correct
information about the interior.

01:31:58.510 --> 01:32:02.740
So again, he's saying,
"Yes, I'm being cautious."

01:32:02.740 --> 01:32:06.170 position:56%
But he's also talking about the map.

01:32:06.170 --> 01:32:09.580
He's saying that in the
absence of regular surveys,

01:32:09.580 --> 01:32:12.960
the maps supplied were
necessarily untrustworthy.

01:32:12.960 --> 01:32:18.930
What he means is the only maps
that were available were yes,

01:32:18.930 --> 01:32:21.230
inaccurate, but that's all we had.

01:32:21.230 --> 01:32:26.110
That's the necessary inaccuracy
here with respect to the ground.

01:32:26.110 --> 01:32:31.120
So Callwell is saying, "Hamilton,
you're overstating this."

01:32:31.120 --> 01:32:35.050
Let's see whether what's
being said is true.

01:32:35.050 --> 01:32:39.110
Okay, so let's examine to the
components of the briefing.

01:32:39.110 --> 01:32:44.010
The War Office secret report on
certain many places in Turkey.

01:32:44.010 --> 01:32:47.320
Remember Hamilton saying, you know,
"I didn't have any information.

01:32:47.320 --> 01:32:48.620
I didn't know where to go.

01:32:48.620 --> 01:32:52.750 position:56%
I didn't have anything that would
allow me to land in Constantinople."

01:32:52.750 --> 01:32:54.810
Well, what about the map?

01:32:54.810 --> 01:33:01.060 position:56%
The War Office map, the Geographical
Section of the General Staff 2285,

01:33:01.060 --> 01:33:06.880
1908 map, the map of the
Peninsula of Gallipoli.

01:33:06.880 --> 01:33:09.690
Okay, so let's look at
"Certain Many Places in Turkey."

01:33:09.690 --> 01:33:15.330
This is a fat, big
report with two sections.

01:33:15.330 --> 01:33:19.900
He was drawn up in response to
one of the many, many disputes.

01:33:19.900 --> 01:33:23.910
This one the Aqaba Crisis
of 1906, which is a dispute

01:33:23.910 --> 01:33:28.730 position:56%
between drawing the boundary between
Egypt and Syria -- sounds familiar.

01:33:28.730 --> 01:33:34.360
The diplomatic argument between
Britain and the Ottoman Empire,

01:33:34.360 --> 01:33:38.150
which meant that they needed
maps to provide information

01:33:38.150 --> 01:33:41.090
for any future boots on the ground.

01:33:41.090 --> 01:33:45.600
A report which has
lots of information

01:33:45.600 --> 01:33:49.800 position:56%
about the Gallipoli Peninsula, about
locations there in the Dardanelles,

01:33:49.800 --> 01:33:54.760
the Dardanelles itself, and
the Buliar lines as mentioned.

01:33:54.760 --> 01:34:00.450
It's a book that Hamilton is
saying has barely any information,

01:34:00.450 --> 01:34:04.440
and yet we have maps and
plans really valuable,

01:34:04.440 --> 01:34:06.850
lots of detail here.

01:34:06.850 --> 01:34:08.310
And topographical panoramas.

01:34:08.310 --> 01:34:12.270
You remember this is an amphibious
landing, and for sure what you want

01:34:12.270 --> 01:34:16.040
to see is what you see from
the sea, moving on to the land.

01:34:16.040 --> 01:34:18.250
And so, there's topographical
panoramas.

01:34:18.250 --> 01:34:25.310 position:56%
We also have the very, very detailed
specifics of fortifications.

01:34:25.310 --> 01:34:31.120
This is Seddel Bahr, at the
entrance to the Dardanelles.

01:34:31.120 --> 01:34:34.420
And panoramic photographs
with annotations,

01:34:34.420 --> 01:34:36.390
once again providing information.

01:34:36.390 --> 01:34:40.450
Let's remember, this is 1914,
1915 that this is being operated.

01:34:40.450 --> 01:34:45.510 position:56%
This had been developed in 1909,
we're not a long way from the detail

01:34:45.510 --> 01:34:48.540
that we can provide in
1916 [inaudible], again,

01:34:48.540 --> 01:34:51.280
as Ryan has explained to us.

01:34:51.280 --> 01:34:54.750
Okay, so was this information
any good?

01:34:54.750 --> 01:34:56.760
Well, the report gave
all the details

01:34:56.760 --> 01:34:58.960
of the batteries, of the defenses.

01:34:58.960 --> 01:35:00.640
So sure, it's good.

01:35:00.640 --> 01:35:04.520
It also identified the nature
of the terrain from the sea.

01:35:04.520 --> 01:35:05.820
Well, it's an amphibious landing.

01:35:05.820 --> 01:35:07.330
That's what you want.

01:35:07.330 --> 01:35:11.120
And for sure, it influenced the
choice of the landing beaches,

01:35:11.120 --> 01:35:13.010
and Hamilton deployed
that information.

01:35:13.010 --> 01:35:16.820
And yet, Hamilton postwar is saying
he didn't have enough information.

01:35:16.820 --> 01:35:21.490
Well, he certainly
used that information.

01:35:21.490 --> 01:35:24.480
What about maps?

01:35:24.480 --> 01:35:26.930
Maps that the Phillips Society
and the Library of Congress

01:35:26.930 --> 01:35:31.890
who I'm very grateful to for
bringing me here to do this,

01:35:31.890 --> 01:35:33.410
a great honor for me
to talk about it.

01:35:33.410 --> 01:35:35.740
Let's look at that map.

01:35:35.740 --> 01:35:40.940
Yet another product of the
Aqaba Crisis, derived though

01:35:40.940 --> 01:35:46.550
from an earlier survey, a survey
made by the French in 1854.

01:35:46.550 --> 01:35:51.350
I will pronounce this
particularly well,

01:35:51.350 --> 01:35:53.840
but it's the "Carte de la
Presqu'lle de Gallipoli,"

01:35:53.840 --> 01:35:56.200
okay, produced in 1854.

01:35:56.200 --> 01:35:59.820
We've heard again from Ryan about
what was available to the allies

01:35:59.820 --> 01:36:05.210
in 1914 and '15 in France, a
map of similar quality to this.

01:36:05.210 --> 01:36:09.500
This had been surveyed in
1854 during the Crimean War,

01:36:09.500 --> 01:36:11.620
and this is a 1 to 50,000 scale.

01:36:11.620 --> 01:36:15.510
So actually, this is a larger
scale map that had been produced

01:36:15.510 --> 01:36:19.970
for the mainland of France,
constructed most likely

01:36:19.970 --> 01:36:22.860
with theodolite and plane
table to give the angles,

01:36:22.860 --> 01:36:24.950
to get the locations, similar

01:36:24.950 --> 01:36:27.300
to domestic survey
that was carried out.

01:36:27.300 --> 01:36:32.150
And at a scale of 1 to 50,000, it
had contour intervals of 10 meters,

01:36:32.150 --> 01:36:36.820
giving you a map which has
a fair amount of detail.

01:36:36.820 --> 01:36:40.740
So let's look at this map.

01:36:40.740 --> 01:36:42.110
It's fairly handsome.

01:36:42.110 --> 01:36:44.010
It's black and white.

01:36:44.010 --> 01:36:48.380
Those of you in the audience
who are acquainted with that,

01:36:48.380 --> 01:36:51.750
which I would count as
everybody, would understand

01:36:51.750 --> 01:36:55.620
that this map is telling you this
is a tough terrain to work on.

01:36:55.620 --> 01:36:58.330
Straightaway, you are
identifying the ruggedness

01:36:58.330 --> 01:37:00.490
of the terrain by the
contour interval.

01:37:00.490 --> 01:37:02.150
You're picking out the readings.

01:37:02.150 --> 01:37:05.260
You're picking out the way in
which the water is flowing.

01:37:05.260 --> 01:37:09.870
Across here, you can see the
gray location of high points.

01:37:09.870 --> 01:37:12.190
There are terrain annotations here.

01:37:12.190 --> 01:37:14.010
There is a feature
called Gully Ravine

01:37:14.010 --> 01:37:16.960
which became a major
part of the battle.

01:37:16.960 --> 01:37:19.830
And we can see here Achi Baba,

01:37:19.830 --> 01:37:25.290
a location which became a British
obsession but never, ever taken.

01:37:25.290 --> 01:37:26.700
I spoke to Turks on the ground.

01:37:26.700 --> 01:37:28.740
They said this would be Verdun.

01:37:28.740 --> 01:37:30.750
The British would never take this.

01:37:30.750 --> 01:37:34.960
It was always going to
be in Ottoman hands.

01:37:34.960 --> 01:37:39.160
So, at 1 to 50,000 scale,
equivalent in quality.

01:37:39.160 --> 01:37:42.620
Was this really the map
that has no information

01:37:42.620 --> 01:37:45.240
that Hamilton is talking about?

01:37:45.240 --> 01:37:47.630
Well, to be fair, we're
looking at something

01:37:47.630 --> 01:37:49.670
that the British thought
they could improve on,

01:37:49.670 --> 01:37:52.240
which is probably a bad thing.

01:37:52.240 --> 01:37:56.480
That map was regularized.

01:37:56.480 --> 01:38:00.810
The British wanted it to
be 1 inch to 1 mile 1 mile.

01:38:00.810 --> 01:38:04.390
You measure an inch, on
your map you've gone a mile.

01:38:04.390 --> 01:38:11.550 position:56%
So they make this really strange
adjustment to 1 to 63,360 scale map.

01:38:11.550 --> 01:38:15.110
And they also increase
the contour interval

01:38:15.110 --> 01:38:18.290
to 31 meters, a hundred feet.

01:38:18.290 --> 01:38:22.450
That immediately creates something
which looks much more open,

01:38:22.450 --> 01:38:24.110
perhaps difficult to
see in this light,

01:38:24.110 --> 01:38:26.900
but you can see how there
are fewer contours here.

01:38:26.900 --> 01:38:30.460
Now you, as experienced
individuals, will know full well

01:38:30.460 --> 01:38:35.130
that even this map has information
upon it because these contour lines

01:38:35.130 --> 01:38:38.180
at a hundred meters separation
still quite close together,

01:38:38.180 --> 01:38:41.900
still picking out a ravine, still
picking out the major points.

01:38:41.900 --> 01:38:43.200
So this is Gully Ravine.

01:38:43.200 --> 01:38:44.530
This is Achi Baba.

01:38:44.530 --> 01:38:47.530
There are terrain annotations
on the full sheet also,

01:38:47.530 --> 01:38:50.000
so it is giving information.

01:38:50.000 --> 01:38:54.660
But the change in scale
does cause problems,

01:38:54.660 --> 01:38:57.400
and those subdue the
terrain features.

01:38:57.400 --> 01:38:59.350
So I've talked a lot about
the mythology of the map,

01:38:59.350 --> 01:39:01.880
but maybe now I am erring
towards -- Well, hold on a minute,

01:39:01.880 --> 01:39:08.330
maybe this map is not as
good as I had first made out.

01:39:08.330 --> 01:39:10.190
Was it valuable?

01:39:10.190 --> 01:39:13.600
And there's a corrective that I
have to point out to you here.

01:39:13.600 --> 01:39:17.000
Well, the map depicted the same
features as the French one before.

01:39:17.000 --> 01:39:20.710
The French one was still
available to the British.

01:39:20.710 --> 01:39:23.080
The French map was
the only medium --

01:39:23.080 --> 01:39:25.880
I would call it necessarily a large
scale map -- that was available.

01:39:25.880 --> 01:39:28.510
There was no choice but to use it.

01:39:28.510 --> 01:39:29.810
You can't conjure up.

01:39:29.810 --> 01:39:31.280
You can't do a satellite survey.

