You can't conjure up an
aerial photographic sweep.

01:39:34.640 --> 01:39:36.030
This was enemy territory.

01:39:36.030 --> 01:39:40.500
And by the way, we're talking about
1914-1915 where your aircraft,

01:39:40.500 --> 01:39:43.450
as Ryan has pointed out,
are very, very flimsy.

01:39:43.450 --> 01:39:46.220
But the problem was
that the redrawing

01:39:46.220 --> 01:39:49.770
of this map created the
mythology of the scapegoat,

01:39:49.770 --> 01:39:53.950
that this had an effect of subduing
the features of the landscape.

01:39:53.950 --> 01:39:56.090
Okay, great.

01:39:56.090 --> 01:39:59.130 position:56%
I'm thinking, okay, well, why didn't
they just use some other maps?

01:39:59.130 --> 01:40:02.070
You know, if that one's no
good, use something else.

01:40:02.070 --> 01:40:05.730
Maybe the story about
them combing the bookshops

01:40:05.730 --> 01:40:08.250
in Alexandria was correct.

01:40:08.250 --> 01:40:09.940
To be honest, what
map are available?

01:40:09.940 --> 01:40:12.240
Hardly any, if any.

01:40:14.240 --> 01:40:18.520
There are some prewar surveys
carried out by British military

01:40:18.520 --> 01:40:24.820
and naval officers, often
surreptitiously, clandestine,

01:40:24.820 --> 01:40:28.730
because of these crises
that I've mentioned.

01:40:28.730 --> 01:40:31.960
There was a single
small-scale location map,

01:40:31.960 --> 01:40:39.260
very similar to the image I
showed you of the satellite scale.

01:40:39.260 --> 01:40:45.190
And tellingly, there were
no large-scale Ottoman maps.

01:40:45.190 --> 01:40:48.140
So, not even the Ottomans
had a map, be it to a scale

01:40:48.140 --> 01:40:50.990
that could be used
in a military sense.

01:40:50.990 --> 01:40:57.200 position:56%
The 1 to 25,000 survey, very similar
to the scales used for military maps

01:40:57.200 --> 01:41:01.250
that Ryan has referred to, was
completed only on the eve of war.

01:41:01.250 --> 01:41:06.770
So that meant that
the British 1 inch map

01:41:06.770 --> 01:41:11.110
and its derivatives was the only
map available to the Allies,

01:41:11.110 --> 01:41:15.830
so bemoaning it is yes, it
is a difficult map to use

01:41:15.830 --> 01:41:17.130
but it's the only one you've got.

01:41:17.130 --> 01:41:20.650
So if it's the only one
you've got, get on and use it.

01:41:20.650 --> 01:41:21.950
Okay, so here you go.

01:41:21.950 --> 01:41:24.310
This is what's known as
the quarter inch map.

01:41:24.310 --> 01:41:28.860
This is the map that
shows 1 to 250,000 scale.

01:41:28.860 --> 01:41:31.960
It's pretty useful and that
it shows you how Gallipoli

01:41:31.960 --> 01:41:35.130
and the Peninsula works in
the Dardanelle Straights.

01:41:35.130 --> 01:41:39.490
It was printed in 1908, so again,
it's a derivative of those maps

01:41:39.490 --> 01:41:41.600
and its strategic, not tactical.

01:41:41.600 --> 01:41:44.070
We've heard this again from Ryan,

01:41:44.070 --> 01:41:47.970
in that different maps
are doing different jobs.

01:41:47.970 --> 01:41:52.610
This was issued to the British
forces because it gave them an idea

01:41:52.610 --> 01:41:56.370 position:56%
of where they were in the world,
and therefore they needed to be able

01:41:56.370 --> 01:41:58.540
to get larger scale
maps to work it out.

01:41:58.540 --> 01:42:01.200
It still was used though,
as you can see here,

01:42:01.200 --> 01:42:04.070
with the little red annotations
showing the landing beaches

01:42:04.070 --> 01:42:05.370 position:56%
in the southern part of [Inaudible].

01:42:05.370 --> 01:42:09.860
Okay, what about the older surveys?

01:42:09.860 --> 01:42:12.470
These are the ones
surreptitiously carried out

01:42:12.470 --> 01:42:16.310
or done under diplomatic cover.

01:42:16.310 --> 01:42:23.090 position:56%
There was one by Captain Grover of
the British Royal Engineers in 1876.

01:42:23.090 --> 01:42:27.610
Grover was operating under
diplomatic support because, again,

01:42:27.610 --> 01:42:32.340
the British and French were allied
to the Ottomans at this point.

01:42:32.340 --> 01:42:36.800
There were also surveys of
the Bulair lines, these very,

01:42:36.800 --> 01:42:42.060 position:56%
very important fortifications across
the narrowest part of that location.

01:42:42.060 --> 01:42:43.900
So there was lots of that
information available.

01:42:43.900 --> 01:42:47.830
I want to take you to
looking at Grover's survey.

01:42:47.830 --> 01:42:51.360
This is entirely prescient,
because what Grover is talking

01:42:51.360 --> 01:42:54.070
about are some of the
landing beaches,

01:42:54.070 --> 01:42:57.830 position:56%
because those landing beaches which
had appeared in the reports early on

01:42:57.830 --> 01:43:01.900
and the reports in 1909 were
the self-same landing beaches

01:43:01.900 --> 01:43:03.200
that would be used again.

01:43:03.200 --> 01:43:06.100
The reason for that is,
they're the only landing beaches

01:43:06.100 --> 01:43:08.910
on this rugged terrain.

01:43:08.910 --> 01:43:12.780
So Grover carried out a rapid
reconnaissance of the coastline

01:43:12.780 --> 01:43:16.320
between two locations that
will become familiar to you.

01:43:16.320 --> 01:43:21.230
This place Gaba Tepe here, and this
location here, Fisherman's Hut,

01:43:21.230 --> 01:43:24.430
which still exists
today on this coast.

01:43:25.480 --> 01:43:27.510
If you look at this,
we can see something

01:43:27.510 --> 01:43:29.520
which looks fairly impressive.

01:43:29.520 --> 01:43:36.150
It's a scale of 4 inches to a
mile, 1 to 15,000 plus or minus.

01:43:36.150 --> 01:43:40.620
But what we get is a sense of
the rapidity of the mapping here.

01:43:40.620 --> 01:43:42.830
It's a stylized form.

01:43:42.830 --> 01:43:46.820
We don't see very much
the rugged terrain

01:43:46.820 --> 01:43:49.200
that I will demonstrate
to you in a moment.

01:43:49.200 --> 01:43:53.140
We're getting really a sense of
this relatively smooth point.

01:43:53.140 --> 01:43:55.580
This is the heights to Sari Bair,

01:43:55.580 --> 01:43:59.210
which is a mountain
area in this location.

01:43:59.210 --> 01:44:03.000
So, getting a sense of
stylized, smoothed contours,

01:44:03.000 --> 01:44:08.330
really done in haste, but we do
have topographical annotations.

01:44:08.330 --> 01:44:13.550
Scrub, impossible cliffs, difficult
beaches, precipitous cliffs,

01:44:13.550 --> 01:44:19.740
that kind of thing -- all of
which was available to Hamilton.

01:44:19.740 --> 01:44:22.570
So, I've mentioned about the maps

01:44:22.570 --> 01:44:25.100
that were produced
on the eve of war.

01:44:25.100 --> 01:44:29.990
And here we have an Ottoman map
with a beautiful Ottoman script --

01:44:29.990 --> 01:44:33.630
Ottoman calligraphy, of course, is
amongst the finest in the world.

01:44:33.630 --> 01:44:37.210
And what we see here is the
map of the Cape Helles area

01:44:37.210 --> 01:44:42.080
that was once reputedly owned
by General Liman von Sanders,

01:44:42.080 --> 01:44:46.530
the German commander of the
Ottoman troops in this location.

01:44:46.530 --> 01:44:49.740
This resides in the National
Archives in the United Kingdom

01:44:49.740 --> 01:44:53.990
and the originals in the
equivalent in Australia.

01:44:53.990 --> 01:44:57.960
This emphasizes the fact that these
maps might have been available

01:44:57.960 --> 01:45:00.960
to somebody as senior
as Liman von Sanders,

01:45:00.960 --> 01:45:03.050
but they were just not available

01:45:03.050 --> 01:45:06.090
to the British, French,
or other allies.

01:45:06.090 --> 01:45:11.310
The reason for that is, they were
literally surveyed between 1912

01:45:11.310 --> 01:45:18.330
and 1914, and the issue of them
was probably only in 1914 and 1915.

01:45:18.330 --> 01:45:21.620
So, pretty much they're having some
intelligence services that have

01:45:21.620 --> 01:45:24.050
to do a lot of hard work
to get a hold of these maps

01:45:24.050 --> 01:45:28.640
if they had not actually yet
been issued to their own troops.

01:45:28.640 --> 01:45:32.110
So once again, we have the
only map that's available

01:45:32.110 --> 01:45:40.370
to the Allies is the ill-fated
and godforsaken 1 inch map.

01:45:40.370 --> 01:45:44.140 position:56%
Okay, so what I want to do now is to
take you in more detail down to two

01:45:44.140 --> 01:45:48.310
of the main locations of
the Gallipoli Peninsula.

01:45:48.310 --> 01:45:55.240
We're talking about what is now
known as Anzac Day, April 25, 1915,

01:45:55.240 --> 01:46:00.220
when the landings were made
of the wild colonial boys

01:46:00.220 --> 01:46:02.720
of the Australians
and New Zealanders.

01:46:02.720 --> 01:46:08.790
They were the ill-prepared,
unpracticed, untested troops

01:46:08.790 --> 01:46:12.410
with a little bit of
colonial verve sent to fight

01:46:12.410 --> 01:46:15.390
up these really difficult terrain.

01:46:15.390 --> 01:46:21.770
In the South, the British 29th
division, professional troops,

01:46:21.770 --> 01:46:25.210
fought long and hard in
Britain's small wars,

01:46:25.210 --> 01:46:29.000
sent to take the biggest
nut to crack at Cape Helles.

01:46:29.000 --> 01:46:34.860
An idea behind them was to rise
up the high ground, join forces,

01:46:34.860 --> 01:46:41.230
[inaudible], dispose of the guns
and dispose of the minefields.

01:46:41.230 --> 01:46:42.550
That's the idea behind it.

01:46:42.550 --> 01:46:46.480
The terrain here is
different in both locations.

01:46:48.710 --> 01:46:52.520
So, this wonderful spot -- I had
to Photoshop my son out of this

01:46:52.520 --> 01:46:57.180
to make it look more military,
but he was only a little boy then.

01:46:57.180 --> 01:47:03.050
This wonderful spot, a magnificent
beach, is very similar in many ways

01:47:03.050 --> 01:47:07.160
to the killing beaches of Omaha.

01:47:07.160 --> 01:47:11.540
We have cliffs, we have
narrow slot-like drawers,

01:47:11.540 --> 01:47:14.330
as the Americans would call
them after Omaha Beach.

01:47:14.330 --> 01:47:17.660
And we would imagine here
the men coming ashore,

01:47:17.660 --> 01:47:20.560
wading ashore here
into the face of hell.

01:47:20.560 --> 01:47:27.340 position:56%
So, what was the plan at Helles,
sending the most experienced troops?

01:47:27.340 --> 01:47:29.550
Well, it was to split the force

01:47:29.550 --> 01:47:36.700
because what we have is Hamilton
has a large force of 80,000,

01:47:36.700 --> 01:47:39.820
but not large enough really
to take the Peninsula.

01:47:39.820 --> 01:47:41.120
I'll come into that in a moment.

01:47:41.120 --> 01:47:45.160
He split them according to
these very, very small beaches.

01:47:45.160 --> 01:47:47.200
They were narrow, they
were constraining.

01:47:47.200 --> 01:47:51.090
They were that way inclined
because of the drainage each went

01:47:51.090 --> 01:47:56.700
in a rectilinear pattern,
down the line of the Peninsula

01:47:56.700 --> 01:47:58.210
because it's lining
up with the faults,

01:47:58.210 --> 01:48:01.990
the fractures, the
tectonic features.

01:48:01.990 --> 01:48:04.410
We can see an open -- what
we could call a glacis,

01:48:04.410 --> 01:48:07.430
very typical of any fortification.

01:48:07.430 --> 01:48:10.890
And we can see the rising
ground, and the idea here is

01:48:10.890 --> 01:48:14.900
that there are no artillery
pieces being landed at this point.

01:48:14.900 --> 01:48:16.950
It's an amphibious landing.

01:48:16.950 --> 01:48:18.510
There are no tanks.

01:48:18.510 --> 01:48:20.680
There is no chance of
bringing field guns.

01:48:20.680 --> 01:48:22.350
You need the Navy to do their job.

01:48:22.350 --> 01:48:25.080
A naval gunnery is low trajectory.

01:48:25.080 --> 01:48:26.980
So you've got a low-rising slope.

01:48:26.980 --> 01:48:30.800
You can hopefully sweep
that with those guns.

01:48:30.800 --> 01:48:35.160
The idea behind it -- to get to the
prize of dominating the narrows,

01:48:35.160 --> 01:48:40.850
of allowing those Navy
boys to get through.

01:48:40.850 --> 01:48:45.840
But that's assuming that
nothing is happening on land.

01:48:45.840 --> 01:48:50.620
And so, Hamilton is
writing almost begrudgingly,

01:48:50.620 --> 01:48:53.970
how dare they organize for defense?

01:48:53.970 --> 01:48:57.210
"The Peninsula is being fortified
and many Turks work every night

01:48:57.210 --> 01:48:59.120
on trenches, redoubts,
and entanglements."

01:48:59.120 --> 01:49:02.110
How dare they?

01:49:02.110 --> 01:49:04.780
Because the Turks and the Germans

01:49:04.780 --> 01:49:07.730
who are operating here
knew what they were doing.

01:49:07.730 --> 01:49:11.890
The Turks have fought many wars
before this -- the Balkan wars.

01:49:11.890 --> 01:49:13.780
They had fought against
the Italians.

01:49:13.780 --> 01:49:15.100
They fought against the Bulgarians.

01:49:15.100 --> 01:49:17.660
They fought against everybody, and
they had lost a lot of territory.

01:49:17.660 --> 01:49:20.080 position:56%
So they were fairly battle hardened.

01:49:20.080 --> 01:49:21.490
They knew what they were doing.

01:49:21.490 --> 01:49:26.240
The trench lines here were
following the contours.

01:49:26.240 --> 01:49:30.300
There were strong points,
machine-gun posts, barbed wire put

01:49:30.300 --> 01:49:33.190
in position to stop the
troops coming ashore.

01:49:33.190 --> 01:49:35.240
There were hillsides.

01:49:35.240 --> 01:49:39.140
Again, very, very similar to
the kinds of fortifications

01:49:39.140 --> 01:49:41.750
that were put in place
before Normandy,

01:49:41.750 --> 01:49:48.280
with Rommel placing his defensive
positions on those D-Day beaches.

01:49:48.280 --> 01:49:49.860
So, the Turks were ready.

01:49:49.860 --> 01:49:53.660
They were also capable and
they were able, of course,

01:49:53.660 --> 01:49:56.730
to use the terrain effectively.

01:49:58.420 --> 01:50:01.430
So that meant that the
1 inch map, of course,

01:50:01.430 --> 01:50:04.040
needed extra embellishment.

01:50:04.040 --> 01:50:05.980
So there were reconnaissance
sketches.

01:50:05.980 --> 01:50:08.490
Here's a reconnaissance sketch
in the National Archives

01:50:08.490 --> 01:50:12.490
in the UK showing some
interpretation

01:50:12.490 --> 01:50:15.490
on the map -- very much sketchy.

01:50:15.490 --> 01:50:19.420
And there were also aerial
interpretations literally

01:50:19.420 --> 01:50:24.880
with an aviator in a very, very
rudimentary aircraft with a map

01:50:24.880 --> 01:50:29.390
on his lap, drawing on the position
of trenches and other things,

01:50:29.390 --> 01:50:31.140
because we're not getting
aerial photography

01:50:31.140 --> 01:50:35.320
at this particular
stage of the campaign.

01:50:35.320 --> 01:50:36.890
Yes, we have panoramic sketches

01:50:36.890 --> 01:50:40.310
because every military
officer today, as then,

01:50:40.310 --> 01:50:43.240
was trained in the art
of panoramic sketching.

01:50:43.240 --> 01:50:46.740
And we can see just how difficult
these individual landing beaches

01:50:46.740 --> 01:50:50.080
would be in the face
of such a terrain.

01:50:50.080 --> 01:50:56.040
Now, I want to look at the map.

01:50:56.040 --> 01:50:57.710
I've said about this a mythology.

01:50:57.710 --> 01:50:59.920
I sort of overemphasized that.

01:50:59.920 --> 01:51:02.450
Let's actually now take
a more objective view.

01:51:02.450 --> 01:51:04.490
Did the map do its job?

01:51:04.490 --> 01:51:06.770
Well, here's the French one.

01:51:06.770 --> 01:51:08.940
This is at the tip
of the Dardanelles.

01:51:08.940 --> 01:51:11.520
And here's the British one.

01:51:11.520 --> 01:51:17.520
And I think as you'll see, there's
a change in the view of that map.

01:51:17.520 --> 01:51:20.980
What we have is a much
more open terrain.

01:51:20.980 --> 01:51:25.900
Doesn't seem to have the same
level of detail as the French one.

01:51:25.900 --> 01:51:29.200
That's because of the contouring
and the change in scale.

01:51:29.200 --> 01:51:36.880 position:56%
We can see one or two hill features,
Hill 114, Hill 138, and Hill 141.

01:51:36.880 --> 01:51:39.420 position:56%
These were all named by the British.

01:51:39.420 --> 01:51:42.290
On the French, we can
pick out contouring.

01:51:42.290 --> 01:51:44.740
It gives us a sense of
the hills and [inaudible].

01:51:44.740 --> 01:51:48.550
On the British, just spot heights.

01:51:48.550 --> 01:51:50.780
I should also point
out that each one

01:51:50.780 --> 01:51:56.380
of the beaches is a concave
situation, and if you look

01:51:56.380 --> 01:52:01.480 position:56%
in any manual of amphibious warfare,
you avoid these like the plague

01:52:01.480 --> 01:52:05.770
because they create
[inaudible] fire from two sides.

01:52:07.150 --> 01:52:11.700
There's also just about picked
out on the French one a kind

01:52:11.700 --> 01:52:13.750
of feature known as Guezi Baba,

01:52:13.750 --> 01:52:17.140
which is totally absent
on the British map.

01:52:17.140 --> 01:52:20.040
Why does this matter?

01:52:20.040 --> 01:52:24.200
Well, let's look at one of the
maps that was captured in April

01:52:24.200 --> 01:52:27.870
and May 1915 as the
Allies started to land.

01:52:27.870 --> 01:52:31.930
This is an Ottoman map, mapped
to the scale of 1 to 25,000.

01:52:31.930 --> 01:52:34.830
British cartographers looked
at this and said, "Yeah,

01:52:34.830 --> 01:52:39.560
it looks a little bit too good
to be true, but pretty accurate."

01:52:39.560 --> 01:52:41.770
We can see all of the
features on here.

01:52:41.770 --> 01:52:45.090
Hill 114 with nice contouring.

01:52:45.090 --> 01:52:47.990
Hill 138, similar kind
of contouring.

01:52:47.990 --> 01:52:52.430
We see that Hill 138
and Guezi Baba nearby,

01:52:52.430 --> 01:52:55.130
part of a similar terrain feature.

01:52:55.130 --> 01:53:00.600
That was completely missed on
the maps and the annotations.

01:53:00.600 --> 01:53:07.070
But let's not forget these maps
were not available to the Allies.

01:53:07.070 --> 01:53:08.510
So what is this matter?

01:53:08.510 --> 01:53:11.680
Well, this is a map that was
carried out by Commander Douglas.

01:53:11.680 --> 01:53:14.260
He was a naval commander
and cartographer.

01:53:14.260 --> 01:53:17.240
He did a survey post war --

01:53:17.240 --> 01:53:21.410
well, post to the initial landings
during the campaign to give a sense

01:53:21.410 --> 01:53:22.710
of what the British had to face.

01:53:22.710 --> 01:53:25.950
There was a lot of sort of
recrimination and discussion.

01:53:25.950 --> 01:53:28.760
He puts on all of the trench lines.

01:53:28.760 --> 01:53:33.330
He shows the point that has the
British land at W and V beaches.

01:53:33.330 --> 01:53:36.460
The intention was that they
would join up and join forces,

01:53:36.460 --> 01:53:40.860
also with men coming ashore here
which I haven't put on -- X beach.

01:53:40.860 --> 01:53:45.980
They would then take the Turks in
the rear there, remove the threat,

01:53:45.980 --> 01:53:48.530
and push on up the Peninsula.

01:53:48.530 --> 01:53:52.090
But what's been forgotten
here is the effect

01:53:52.090 --> 01:53:55.120
of that missing fortification.

01:53:55.120 --> 01:53:59.180
So yes, the map failed
in this instance.

01:53:59.180 --> 01:54:02.030
So, let's look at that.

01:54:02.030 --> 01:54:07.780
We can see here the concavity
of that, the bowl shape,

01:54:07.780 --> 01:54:10.190
the sense that the
trenches built by the Turks.

01:54:10.190 --> 01:54:15.670
Follow the line of that
bowl, with the obvious effect

01:54:15.670 --> 01:54:19.310
that when the British
landed, they thought,

01:54:19.310 --> 01:54:20.610
"Right, there's no fire here.

01:54:20.610 --> 01:54:21.910
Everything's fine."

01:54:21.910 --> 01:54:25.670
As soon as they got on the beach,
the Turks used their [inaudible],

01:54:25.670 --> 01:54:27.750
their knowledge, their experience.

01:54:27.750 --> 01:54:30.350
Held their fire until
the British were ashore,

01:54:30.350 --> 01:54:34.350
and poured fire into those men.

01:54:34.350 --> 01:54:37.040 position:56%
From Guezi Baba over here, Hill 141,

01:54:37.040 --> 01:54:40.560
and from the line of
the Turkish trenches.

01:54:40.560 --> 01:54:44.060
The same is true here at W Beach.

01:54:44.060 --> 01:54:45.840
Limestone outcrops.

01:54:45.840 --> 01:54:47.990
This is a line of dunes here.

01:54:47.990 --> 01:54:50.100
We can see here the narrow beach.

01:54:50.100 --> 01:54:51.670
All of this had barbed wiring.

01:54:51.670 --> 01:54:56.210
All of these trench lines that
followed this concave area.

01:54:56.210 --> 01:55:00.760
All picked out, of course, on
the reconnaissance surveys.

01:55:00.760 --> 01:55:03.630
And we can see the most
effective kill zone.

01:55:03.630 --> 01:55:07.190
As the men were struggling
through the barbed wire here,

01:55:07.190 --> 01:55:12.410
they were facing an onslaught
of fire to try and get ashore

01:55:12.410 --> 01:55:14.940
and move and move on its way.

01:55:14.940 --> 01:55:18.900
And you can see now, can't you,
why it was and why it still is

01:55:18.900 --> 01:55:21.540
that Gallipoli is studied
by the US Marine Corps

01:55:21.540 --> 01:55:25.620
in considering amphibious landing,
and why this had an element

01:55:25.620 --> 01:55:28.070
on the doctrine of D-Day.

01:55:30.020 --> 01:55:33.620
Okay, so let's shift
away from Helles.

01:55:33.620 --> 01:55:36.310
Yes, the map failed a bit there.

01:55:36.310 --> 01:55:38.660
Let's look at the Anzac territory.

01:55:38.660 --> 01:55:42.720
Badlands, okay, a bit like
South Dakota or Arizona,

01:55:42.720 --> 01:55:45.780
places I've had the honor to
visit in your beautiful country.

01:55:45.780 --> 01:55:49.450
And what we can see here
is the incredible element

01:55:49.450 --> 01:55:51.500
of the landscape here.

01:55:51.500 --> 01:55:54.250
This tortuous land --
doesn't look anything

01:55:54.250 --> 01:55:58.640
like Grover's survey of 1876.

01:55:58.640 --> 01:55:59.940
What was the plan here?

01:55:59.940 --> 01:56:01.240
Difficult to see, I'm afraid,

01:56:01.240 --> 01:56:05.910
but what we can see here is this is
Sari Bair, the range of the hill,

01:56:05.910 --> 01:56:08.710
which is badland topography.

01:56:08.710 --> 01:56:10.040
Another from Gaba Tepe

01:56:10.040 --> 01:56:14.770
to the narrows is a
transport corridor, a valley.

01:56:14.770 --> 01:56:16.070
The Turks knew that.

01:56:16.070 --> 01:56:17.400
They fortified that.

01:56:17.400 --> 01:56:20.450
They created a kill
zone of field artillery.

01:56:20.450 --> 01:56:22.810
They defended that
as far as they could.

01:56:22.810 --> 01:56:25.470
So, there was no way that
the Allies could lend there.

01:56:25.470 --> 01:56:28.260
Instead, the Anzacs would land --

01:56:28.260 --> 01:56:29.890
Remember, they were
the untrained guys

01:56:29.890 --> 01:56:34.640
who felt could be able
to combat the terrain.

01:56:34.640 --> 01:56:38.510
Very few Turks here,
relatively unopposed landing.

01:56:38.510 --> 01:56:43.560
Very much more combined with the
terrain, a difficult challenge

01:56:43.560 --> 01:56:47.490
for the men to get up into
that challenging environment.

01:56:47.490 --> 01:56:50.690
So the idea was that they would
rise up, go on one of these ridges,

01:56:50.690 --> 01:56:55.370
hit the top of that hill,
rise over the top, get down

01:56:55.370 --> 01:56:58.080
and help the other
guys who had landed

01:56:58.080 --> 01:57:00.650
at Helles and take the narrows.

01:57:00.650 --> 01:57:05.170
Okay, so let's look at
one of the mythologies.

01:57:05.170 --> 01:57:07.080
You speak to any Australian.

01:57:07.080 --> 01:57:09.560
They'll tell you how the
British generals failed them.

01:57:09.560 --> 01:57:11.860
They'll tell you how they
landed in the wrong place.

01:57:11.860 --> 01:57:13.410
How the British generals
had no idea.

01:57:13.410 --> 01:57:15.930
Part of the enduring mythology

01:57:15.930 --> 01:57:21.750
of the Australian male
at the current moment.

01:57:21.750 --> 01:57:25.120
So, is there any truth
in that [inaudible]?

01:57:25.120 --> 01:57:31.180
The first, second, and third ridges
-- one here, one there, one there.

01:57:31.180 --> 01:57:33.420
These are going to be important.

01:57:33.420 --> 01:57:38.420
General Hamilton, literary man,
a man who swept his arm and said,

01:57:38.420 --> 01:57:41.220
"Right, we will take this area."

01:57:41.220 --> 01:57:45.430
He is saying, "Let's go
from Gaba Tepe to Suvla Bay.

01:57:45.430 --> 01:57:49.530 position:56%
So he's saying, "Look, chaps, if you
land here can you take the ridge,

01:57:49.530 --> 01:57:52.380
everything will be fine."

01:57:52.380 --> 01:57:58.630
General Braithwaite, his chief of
staff, a bit more constraining.

01:57:58.630 --> 01:58:00.800
"Hold on a minute, Hamilton.

01:58:00.800 --> 01:58:04.310
Our men need some very small
specific landing locations."

01:58:04.310 --> 01:58:07.770
Again, the doctrine of
amphibious landings is you have

01:58:07.770 --> 01:58:10.860
to plan and plan again.

01:58:10.860 --> 01:58:14.000
Now Braithwaite is saying,
"Let's say north of Gaba Tepe,

01:58:14.000 --> 01:58:17.080
which is heavily defended,
to the Fisherman's Hut."

01:58:17.080 --> 01:58:18.380
Remember Grover's survey?

01:58:18.380 --> 01:58:23.600
That area of the Gaba
Tepe to Fisherman's Hut.

01:58:23.600 --> 01:58:26.730
The Admiral, Admiral Thursby,

01:58:26.730 --> 01:58:28.460
on the 10th of April is
saying, "Hold on a minute.

01:58:28.460 --> 01:58:30.040
Let's reduce that a bit."

01:58:30.040 --> 01:58:32.770
Now, I know it's the same in
the US as it is in Britain.

01:58:32.770 --> 01:58:35.340
The Navy doesn't speak to the Army,
the Army doesn't speak to the Navy,

01:58:35.340 --> 01:58:36.640
and the Marine Corps in the middle.

01:58:36.640 --> 01:58:39.140
It's exactly the same
situation happening here.

01:58:39.140 --> 01:58:43.330
So what we're seeing here is that
Thursby is altering the plan.

01:58:43.330 --> 01:58:45.940
He's saying, "Well, let's reduce
the scale of it a little bit,"

01:58:45.940 --> 01:58:49.120
whereas Braithwaite is saying
somewhere between that.

01:58:49.120 --> 01:58:50.790
And Thursby, on the
night of the landings,

01:58:50.790 --> 01:58:52.090
is saying, "I'll tell you what.

01:58:52.090 --> 01:58:53.500
We'll reduce it even further."

01:58:53.500 --> 01:58:55.560
So all of these messages are mixed,

01:58:55.560 --> 01:58:57.910
and nobody is really
getting that message.

01:58:57.910 --> 01:59:00.070
So it means that when
the Anzacs finally land,

01:59:00.070 --> 01:59:01.700
we struggle ashore here in

01:59:01.700 --> 01:59:06.840
yet another concave
location, largely unopposed.

01:59:06.840 --> 01:59:10.080
They then have to fight
their way up the ridges.

01:59:10.080 --> 01:59:14.400
And it's that which is the butt of
contention, because some historians

01:59:14.400 --> 01:59:18.150
or popular writers are
saying that the map failed.

01:59:18.150 --> 01:59:19.900
The British land them
in the wrong place.

01:59:19.900 --> 01:59:21.810
Not only did the British
land them in the place

01:59:21.810 --> 01:59:26.690
which had been long held, the
map accuracy had very little

01:59:26.690 --> 01:59:28.410
to do with the landing place.

01:59:28.410 --> 01:59:31.430
So we can't blame the map.

01:59:31.430 --> 01:59:33.180 position:56%
This look in more detail at the map.

01:59:33.180 --> 01:59:34.880
Let's look at those ridges.

01:59:34.880 --> 01:59:36.180
Okay, there's our French map.

01:59:36.180 --> 01:59:39.840
You can see beautifully detailed.

01:59:39.840 --> 01:59:41.140
Is it accurate?

01:59:41.140 --> 01:59:42.660
Well, that's another question.

01:59:42.660 --> 01:59:47.730
There's our first ridge, second
ridge, and third ridge going

01:59:47.730 --> 01:59:50.710
up [inaudible] to the
ridge top at the Sari Bair.

01:59:50.710 --> 01:59:58.530
The British map in this case, not
massively different to be honest.

01:59:58.530 --> 02:00:03.800
Just a little bit less
detail, but again, first ridge,

02:00:03.800 --> 02:00:05.700
second ridge, third ridge.

02:00:05.700 --> 02:00:09.840
And those ridges feature in
all the British landing plans

02:00:09.840 --> 02:00:13.060
because Australians and New
Zealanders would fight their way

02:00:13.060 --> 02:00:15.410
up these ridges to get to the top.

02:00:15.410 --> 02:00:17.240
Okay, they land here,
get up that ridge.

02:00:17.240 --> 02:00:23.730
If they land here, get up
this one, and this one.

02:00:23.730 --> 02:00:26.900
But the problem is that
the maps that the British

02:00:26.900 --> 02:00:31.050
and the French had didn't pick
out what the Ottoman maps did

02:00:31.050 --> 02:00:34.770
at a scale of 1 to 25,000.

02:00:34.770 --> 02:00:36.900
This is what subsequently
has become known

02:00:36.900 --> 02:00:39.440 position:56%
as Anzac Cove, as it is still today.

02:00:39.440 --> 02:00:41.630
We see the first ridge
there has a plateau,

02:00:41.630 --> 02:00:44.610
now known as Plugges Plateau.

02:00:44.610 --> 02:00:47.000 position:56%
The second ridge also has a plateau.

02:00:47.000 --> 02:00:50.870
These plateaus become very
important because as the Anzacs,

02:00:50.870 --> 02:00:53.980
who have not fought a battle
before, are rushing up the slope

02:00:53.980 --> 02:00:55.880
in darkness, they get
to a bridge top.

02:00:55.880 --> 02:00:57.180
What do they do?

02:00:57.180 --> 02:00:58.480
They dig in.

02:00:58.480 --> 02:01:00.240
Once you've done again, the
battle is, in effect, over,

02:01:00.240 --> 02:01:03.060
because you have to, as
Ryan has pointed out again,

02:01:03.060 --> 02:01:05.910
get out of those trenches and
fight the enemy eventually.

02:01:05.910 --> 02:01:07.220
You can't sit there forever,

02:01:07.220 --> 02:01:10.150
not if you've got a very
precarious beachhead.

02:01:10.150 --> 02:01:13.680
And then, this is the
bone of contention,

02:01:13.680 --> 02:01:16.450
because not only do you have
a plateau on the first ridge,

02:01:16.450 --> 02:01:23.340
you have no means of getting
across because that is impassable.

02:01:23.340 --> 02:01:24.800
There is the razor's edge.

02:01:24.800 --> 02:01:29.790
Believe me, that is the literally
centimeters -- inches wide.

02:01:29.790 --> 02:01:33.080
And so, men trying to get across
here stumbling in the darkness.

02:01:33.080 --> 02:01:34.470
No chance.

02:01:34.470 --> 02:01:37.250
The actual opportunity was lost.

02:01:37.250 --> 02:01:42.810
So stuck on those plateau
tops, the Anzacs would stay

02:01:42.810 --> 02:01:48.120
on those plateau tops
throughout the whole campaign.

02:01:48.120 --> 02:01:52.930
But let's remember, those maps
were not available during the war,

02:01:52.930 --> 02:01:56.420
and are in the planning
stage of the war here.

02:01:56.420 --> 02:02:02.190
And also, there were no aerial
photographs that could depict that.

02:02:02.190 --> 02:02:04.330
So, what I'm saying then,

02:02:04.330 --> 02:02:09.160
is that the battle was really
dependent on the mapping and maps.

02:02:09.160 --> 02:02:11.490
But it was also dependent
on the planning

02:02:11.490 --> 02:02:15.310
that was going into that campaign.

02:02:15.310 --> 02:02:17.110
What became known as the
Battle of the Beaches

02:02:17.110 --> 02:02:21.800
in April 1915 was the
battle or battles

02:02:21.800 --> 02:02:25.670
that lost the Gallipoli campaign.

02:02:25.670 --> 02:02:31.520
Because at Helles and at Anzac,
the tenacity of the troops

02:02:31.520 --> 02:02:35.590
that were facing them, the failure
of the troops to get on shore,

02:02:35.590 --> 02:02:40.610
the loss of speed and the
development of inertia

02:02:40.610 --> 02:02:44.790
as they were starting to be held by
the terrain and the Ottomans meant

02:02:44.790 --> 02:02:49.140
that the stability of
those situations meant

02:02:49.140 --> 02:02:52.320
that the war was effectively lost.

02:02:52.320 --> 02:02:56.970
So, at Helles and at Anzac,
we have beach has established,

02:02:56.970 --> 02:02:59.290
and those beachheads
would have to be supplied.

02:02:59.290 --> 02:03:00.900
They would have to be improved.

02:03:00.900 --> 02:03:04.570
They would have to be therefore
mapped in more greater detail.

02:03:04.570 --> 02:03:08.120
So we're now looking at
the latter part of 1915,

02:03:08.120 --> 02:03:11.110
when on the Western front,
new techniques were starting

02:03:11.110 --> 02:03:15.240
to be derived, starting to be
considered in terms of mapping.

02:03:15.240 --> 02:03:20.190
They had some sense of being
able to capture the maps.

02:03:20.190 --> 02:03:22.510
So, what we have here is the new 1

02:03:22.510 --> 02:03:25.990
to 20,000 scale maps based
on Ottoman originals.

02:03:25.990 --> 02:03:28.490
There was a maps officer
that was associated

02:03:28.490 --> 02:03:33.340
with the Egyptian service,
British Army, name of TE Lawrence.

02:03:33.340 --> 02:03:35.970
You might've heard of him
-- Lawrence of Arabia.

02:03:35.970 --> 02:03:39.580
He was involved in the
production of maps there.

02:03:39.580 --> 02:03:41.420
The British took this
very, very seriously

02:03:41.420 --> 02:03:45.470
and created their own series
of 1 to 20,000 scale maps

02:03:45.470 --> 02:03:50.350
with artillery squaring,
again as explained by Ryan.

02:03:50.350 --> 02:03:55.250
There are also aerial
photographic plans.

02:03:55.250 --> 02:03:57.470
We can see the trenches here.

02:03:57.470 --> 02:04:01.300
We can see how this has
been built into a mosaic.

02:04:01.300 --> 02:04:04.650
Photo rectification is very, very
difficult at this stage in the war,

02:04:04.650 --> 02:04:08.520
but these are being used now to
try and match up with each other,

02:04:08.520 --> 02:04:12.700
and we can start to see the
production of sketch maps.

02:04:14.020 --> 02:04:17.020
We also get the production
of mosaic photographic maps,

02:04:17.020 --> 02:04:19.230
which this was done by the
Royal Naval Air Service.

02:04:19.230 --> 02:04:22.230
The British, at that time,
had a Naval Air Service

02:04:22.230 --> 02:04:24.980
and an Army Air Service, and
they were obviously still

02:04:24.980 --> 02:04:26.280
not cooperating.

02:04:26.280 --> 02:04:30.210
But anyway, what we're
seeing here is a production

02:04:30.210 --> 02:04:36.140
of an aerial photographic map from
this service of the Royal Navy.

02:04:36.140 --> 02:04:39.590
And then we get the
production of trench diagrams.

02:04:39.590 --> 02:04:44.000
We are now going from the broader
scale down to the minutiae.

02:04:44.000 --> 02:04:47.450
We need the largest
possible scale of maps.

02:04:47.450 --> 02:04:50.730
And what we have is the production
of so-called trench diagrams,

02:04:50.730 --> 02:04:54.330 position:56%
which are precursors to trench maps.

02:04:54.330 --> 02:04:57.780
These trench diagrams are picked
out by aerial photographic survey

02:04:57.780 --> 02:05:01.020
and by trench raids and by
prisoner taking, all those things

02:05:01.020 --> 02:05:04.700
that again Ryan has helped us
understand, at a scale of 6 inches

02:05:04.700 --> 02:05:10.160
to a mile here, which is 1 inch to
29.3 yards, which is interesting.

02:05:10.160 --> 02:05:13.990
We can see all of the
various trenches here,

02:05:13.990 --> 02:05:19.430
all named after a range of
locations and places in Paris

02:05:19.430 --> 02:05:22.700
or wherever it might be, and we
can see the locations of those.

02:05:22.700 --> 02:05:26.750
And that gives rise to the kind of
trench mapping that we start to see

02:05:26.750 --> 02:05:32.310
at this point in the Western
front as the Allies got serious

02:05:32.310 --> 02:05:34.110
about creating trench maps.

02:05:34.110 --> 02:05:38.920
In the trench mapping is actually
a nod towards the realization

02:05:38.920 --> 02:05:41.240
that you are stuck where you are,

02:05:41.240 --> 02:05:44.820
and that every small
point in detail matters.

02:05:44.820 --> 02:05:49.880
It doesn't mean they're
going to win you the war.

02:05:49.880 --> 02:05:55.510
So, the increased survey effort
were pretty much to no avail.

02:05:55.510 --> 02:05:58.680
Trench warfare, from the failure
of the Battle of the Beaches,

02:05:58.680 --> 02:06:00.220
became an attritional battle,

02:06:00.220 --> 02:06:02.790
just the same as we had
on the Western front.

02:06:02.790 --> 02:06:04.400
The inertia had said in.

02:06:04.400 --> 02:06:09.550
What Clausewitz called "friction"
had meant that we are no longer

02:06:09.550 --> 02:06:12.030
in a position to be
able to take the front.

02:06:12.030 --> 02:06:16.310
The frontal assaults, both at Anzac
and at Cape Helles, where thousands

02:06:16.310 --> 02:06:19.370
of men were losing their lives,
not necessarily on the beaches

02:06:19.370 --> 02:06:21.610
of Gallipoli as the US
comic book pointed out,

02:06:21.610 --> 02:06:27.470
but actually in the killing
fields of the peninsula.

02:06:27.470 --> 02:06:30.180
And then, there were new landings.

02:06:30.180 --> 02:06:35.560
In August at Suvla Bay, a complete
and utter disaster, a waste of time

02:06:35.560 --> 02:06:38.850 position:56%
with the most inexperienced
general you could possibly think of,

02:06:38.850 --> 02:06:43.110
simply because that
general was most senior.

02:06:43.110 --> 02:06:48.670
The campaign had been lost
in April, not afterwards.

02:06:48.670 --> 02:06:51.910
And once in April, we are
looking at the loss of that.

02:06:51.910 --> 02:06:53.870
There was nothing else
that could be done.

02:06:53.870 --> 02:06:58.390
No amount of surveying could
win the war for the Allies.

02:06:58.390 --> 02:07:00.930
So to finish up, did Hamilton
have everything he could?

02:07:00.930 --> 02:07:02.230
Well, yes he did.

02:07:02.230 --> 02:07:03.530
He had the maps and the plans.

02:07:03.530 --> 02:07:04.980
They were the best available.

02:07:04.980 --> 02:07:08.050
The maps, the plans
were all that he had.

02:07:08.050 --> 02:07:09.620
There were no new surveys.

02:07:09.620 --> 02:07:12.470
The Ottoman Turks had
them -- nobody else.

02:07:12.470 --> 02:07:14.950
And there was no means
of carrying out a survey.

02:07:14.950 --> 02:07:17.270
So yeah, those maps were done
with the best of intentions

02:07:17.270 --> 02:07:20.520
and the capability of these working

02:07:20.520 --> 02:07:24.030
in a foreign country
with allies perhaps.

02:07:24.030 --> 02:07:27.490
What we can say is, that the maps
themselves were not themselves

02:07:27.490 --> 02:07:29.270
responsible for failure.

02:07:29.270 --> 02:07:33.420
They contributed to it by things
like the missing [inaudible]

02:07:33.420 --> 02:07:35.750
or the location of razor's edge.

02:07:35.750 --> 02:07:39.690
But he can't blame a
map for the failure.

02:07:39.690 --> 02:07:44.330 position:56%
You have to think and be honest, is
that the campaign is not only doomed

02:07:44.330 --> 02:07:47.680
by the geography of this location,

02:07:47.680 --> 02:07:49.700
but it was also failed
by its planners.

02:07:49.700 --> 02:07:57.720
You can't send 80,000 men to face
50,000 to 60,000 men on the ground.

02:07:57.720 --> 02:07:59.420
Normandy, there were three times

02:07:59.420 --> 02:08:03.380
as many Allied troops
as they were German.

02:08:03.380 --> 02:08:06.020
So this was lost for
the want of resources,

02:08:06.020 --> 02:08:11.300
not lost because of a map, and it
was one by its tenacious defenders.

02:08:11.300 --> 02:08:14.540
So it's incumbent upon me to just
say that we must remember all

02:08:14.540 --> 02:08:17.900
of these troops, tenacious
defenders, all of those allies

02:08:17.900 --> 02:08:19.620
who fought in this
beautiful landscape.

