02:11:40.780 --> 02:11:44.130 position:56%
&gt;&gt; This is out of curiosity, not
just for myself but for other people

02:11:44.130 --> 02:11:48.910
who might not be into war
history and know a lot about that.

02:11:48.910 --> 02:11:52.450
Could you talk about exactly
what you mean by failure?

02:11:52.450 --> 02:11:56.470
Because in my mind, there's
failure of the whole campaign,

02:11:56.470 --> 02:12:02.140
but there's also different levels,
of loss of life or equipment.

02:12:02.140 --> 02:12:07.420
And exactly how do
you define failure?

02:12:07.420 --> 02:12:09.090
&gt;&gt; Richard Pflederer:
Who is that addressed to?

02:12:09.090 --> 02:12:10.390
&gt;&gt; Peter Doyle.

02:12:10.390 --> 02:12:11.690
&gt;&gt; Richard Pflederer:
The question is --

02:12:11.690 --> 02:12:12.990
everybody else didn't hear it --

02:12:12.990 --> 02:12:14.780
how would you define
failure of this operation?

02:12:14.780 --> 02:12:17.010
&gt;&gt; Peter Doyle: Well, it
depends who's speaking,

02:12:17.010 --> 02:12:19.660
because from the Ottomans,
this is not a failure.

02:12:19.660 --> 02:12:20.990
This is a success.

02:12:20.990 --> 02:12:28.160
This is celebrated as a great
victory over the Western powers.

02:12:28.160 --> 02:12:33.960
Coming to your actual point, if we
step aside from Gallipoli a moment,

02:12:33.960 --> 02:12:37.550
an argument last year in the
United Kingdom is, was the Battle

02:12:37.550 --> 02:12:39.180 position:56%
of the Somme a success or a failure?

02:12:39.180 --> 02:12:42.170
And in the Battle of the Somme,
as you may or may not know,

02:12:42.170 --> 02:12:45.150
there were 40,000 men
killed on the first day

02:12:45.150 --> 02:12:48.460
of that battle -- 40,000 men.

02:12:48.460 --> 02:12:51.600
So, what we're considering here
is how do you measure success

02:12:51.600 --> 02:12:52.970
and how do you measure failure.

02:12:52.970 --> 02:12:58.480
And in today's military atmosphere,
the loss of 10 men would be seen

02:12:58.480 --> 02:13:00.650
as a massive failure in many ways.

02:13:00.650 --> 02:13:05.530 position:56%
We're looking at what become
acceptable losses to these officers.

02:13:05.530 --> 02:13:09.370
Now, in the Gallipoli campaign,
we break it down a little bit.

02:13:09.370 --> 02:13:11.310
The maps failed --
that's the argument --

02:13:11.310 --> 02:13:15.070
because it didn't provide the
information for the planners to go

02:13:15.070 --> 02:13:16.570
on and win that campaign.

02:13:16.570 --> 02:13:20.470
I'm arguing, well, that's
a scapegoating of the maps.

02:13:20.470 --> 02:13:25.360 position:56%
The campaign failed from the British
and French and Anzac perspective

02:13:25.360 --> 02:13:27.370
because it didn't deliver
the objectives,

02:13:27.370 --> 02:13:30.260
which is to knock the
Ottoman Empire out of the war.

02:13:30.260 --> 02:13:31.890
But lying on those beaches

02:13:31.890 --> 02:13:35.890
and in those hills were
thousands upon thousands of men,

02:13:35.890 --> 02:13:39.450
not only from the British,
Australians, and New Zealanders,

02:13:39.450 --> 02:13:41.850
etc. Also from the Ottoman Empire,

02:13:41.850 --> 02:13:44.900
who lost incredible numbers
of men at that point.

02:13:44.900 --> 02:13:48.230
So on that basis, could you
ever say that a battle that lost

02:13:48.230 --> 02:13:50.140
that many men was a success?

02:13:50.140 --> 02:13:52.900
Possibly not, and maybe I can
bring Ryan into that in relation

02:13:52.900 --> 02:13:59.690 position:56%
to the last battle of the war, where
we see the Americans engaged here.

02:13:59.690 --> 02:14:01.090
Is that a success?

02:14:01.090 --> 02:14:02.390
Did that fail?

02:14:02.390 --> 02:14:03.980
Why was there a commission
to discuss

02:14:03.980 --> 02:14:07.840
that where the general involved
was actually exonerated?

02:14:07.840 --> 02:14:12.940
And Hamilton also was exonerated,
but shunned into the environment.

02:14:12.940 --> 02:14:16.120
So I think we have to be careful
putting a 21st century perspective

02:14:16.120 --> 02:14:17.420
on it.

02:14:17.420 --> 02:14:18.900
It failed because they didn't
achieve their objectives.

02:14:18.900 --> 02:14:22.250
It failed because the maps didn't
possibly do what they wanted to do.

02:14:22.250 --> 02:14:26.920 position:56%
And in terms of a human tragedy, it
was a complete failure, I would say.

02:14:26.920 --> 02:14:31.530
&gt;&gt; Further to that, had those
losses been as great as they were

02:14:31.530 --> 02:14:37.290
in the objective achieved, it
would've been an expensive victory.

02:14:37.290 --> 02:14:40.470
But it is an expensive failure

02:14:40.470 --> 02:14:43.160
because the objective
was not reached

02:14:43.160 --> 02:14:46.000
and the troops were
ultimately [inaudible].

02:14:46.000 --> 02:14:49.180
&gt;&gt; Peter Doyle: And adding
a sort of a rider to that,

02:14:49.180 --> 02:14:51.690
the very fact that the
British and French thought

02:14:51.690 --> 02:14:55.100
that they could send ships through
-- obsolete is the word they used,

02:14:55.100 --> 02:14:57.820
obsolete ships -- It
dawned on the admirals

02:14:57.820 --> 02:15:00.980
that these obsolete ships were
full of non-obsolete sailors,

02:15:00.980 --> 02:15:04.920
and it was at that point that
the campaign was really doomed.

02:15:04.920 --> 02:15:06.310
&gt;&gt; Richard Pflederer: We've got
