[inaudible] and the [inaudible]

02:18:30.340 --> 02:18:34.450
and all the other elements
of the terrain.

02:18:34.450 --> 02:18:38.670
So the argument is that that did
have the material effect on it,

02:18:38.670 --> 02:18:42.540
but the general argument is that
the terrain creates this inertia,

02:18:42.540 --> 02:18:47.040
this friction, that as you are
losing momentum, you're starting

02:18:47.040 --> 02:18:50.490
to consider the opportunity
to dig in.

02:18:50.490 --> 02:18:53.340
And because these men
were inexperienced,

02:18:53.340 --> 02:18:55.030
they started to do that.

02:18:55.030 --> 02:18:57.760
And there were also stragglers
-- this is not talked about.

02:18:57.760 --> 02:19:01.070
I'm not from the Library of
Congress, so I can say it.

02:19:01.070 --> 02:19:03.660
These men straggled back to
the beaches and there was a lot

02:19:03.660 --> 02:19:06.370
of concern from the Commander
Birdwood that they were going

02:19:06.370 --> 02:19:07.830
to completely lose that command.

02:19:07.830 --> 02:19:11.270
And that's where Hamilton
said dig in, dig, dig, dig,

02:19:11.270 --> 02:19:13.840
and dig into you get your security.

02:19:13.840 --> 02:19:16.270
And that's why the Australians
are called diggers in that way.

02:19:16.270 --> 02:19:18.330
&gt;&gt; Richard Pflederer: As a
means of avoiding a retreat.

02:19:18.330 --> 02:19:19.630
&gt;&gt; Peter Doyle: Exactly.

02:19:19.630 --> 02:19:20.930
As a means of holding
on to what that is.

02:19:20.930 --> 02:19:24.800
So the razor's edge did have a role
to play in the terrain had a role

02:19:24.800 --> 02:19:27.910
to play, but you can't blame
the razors' edges the only real

02:19:27.910 --> 02:19:31.120
significant feature
that caused the failure.

